30
00:01:28,880 --> 00:01:32,760
So if you remember,
lecture 1 was all

31
00:01:32,760 --> 00:01:38,120
about introducing the
concept of self-attention.

32
00:01:38,120 --> 00:01:40,080
And if you remember,
what self-attention

33
00:01:40,080 --> 00:01:48,000
is that each token is
attending to all other tokens

34
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:51,140
in the sequence through
this mechanism of attention.

35
00:01:51,140 --> 00:01:57,400
So you have these notations
of queries, keys, and values.

36
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:00,400
So here the idea
is that the query

37
00:02:00,400 --> 00:02:03,960
is going to ask which
other tokens are

38
00:02:03,960 --> 00:02:09,000
most similar to itself by
comparing query and key.

39
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,600
And then once that's
done, basically we

40
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:14,960
will be taking the
associated value.

41
00:02:14,960 --> 00:02:18,480
So we saw that the
self-attention mechanism can

42
00:02:18,480 --> 00:02:22,560
be expressed with this
formula, so softmax

43
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:26,240
of query times key
transpose over square root

44
00:02:26,240 --> 00:02:32,950
of dk times v. So I hope this
formula is familiar for you.

45
00:02:32,950 --> 00:02:36,300
So just know that this
formula is highly optimized.

46
00:02:36,300 --> 00:02:41,760
These are big matrix
multiplications, or hardware,

47
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:48,280
is very capable of doing, it's
very optimized in doing that.

48
00:02:48,280 --> 00:02:51,600
And all of that to
say that we also

49
00:02:51,600 --> 00:02:54,680
introduced the architecture
of the transformer, which

50
00:02:54,680 --> 00:02:57,200
you can see on the right.

51
00:02:57,200 --> 00:03:00,840
So here, if you
remember, the transformer

52
00:03:00,840 --> 00:03:03,520
is composed of two
main components.

53
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:07,680
So the encoder on the
left side and the decoder

54
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:09,920
on the right side.

55
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:12,280
And the transformer
was initially

56
00:03:12,280 --> 00:03:16,600
introduced in the context
of machine translation.

57
00:03:16,600 --> 00:03:18,760
So you can think
of the left side

58
00:03:18,760 --> 00:03:23,200
as processing the input
text in the source language,

59
00:03:23,200 --> 00:03:25,560
say English.

60
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:29,480
And the right side is
responsible for decoding

61
00:03:29,480 --> 00:03:34,880
the translation in a target
language, let's say in French.

62
00:03:34,880 --> 00:03:38,560
And this multi-head
attention layer

63
00:03:38,560 --> 00:03:43,680
is where the self-attention
mechanism happens.

64
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:47,680
And I remember there
was a lot of questions

65
00:03:47,680 --> 00:03:51,700
regarding-- it's called
multi-head attention layer.

66
00:03:51,700 --> 00:03:52,940
So there are several heads.

67
00:03:52,940 --> 00:03:55,720
What does that correspond to?

68
00:03:55,720 --> 00:03:59,440
So in the transformer paper,
which is the "Attention is All

69
00:03:59,440 --> 00:04:03,520
You Need" paper, you
have this figure,

70
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:07,440
which actually represents
each of these heads.

71
00:04:07,440 --> 00:04:13,120
And you can think of each head
as an opportunity for the model

72
00:04:13,120 --> 00:04:18,800
to learn one way of projecting
the input into being

73
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:23,920
a query, a key, or a value.

74
00:04:23,920 --> 00:04:26,340
So just being a bit more
clear, so for instance,

75
00:04:26,340 --> 00:04:29,720
for the query and the key,
so this is like each head.

76
00:04:29,720 --> 00:04:32,680
So the number of
these little boxes

77
00:04:32,680 --> 00:04:36,080
is basically the
number of heads.

78
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:43,760
And to better visualize and
understand what this means,

79
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:46,160
I also wanted to
show I guess what

80
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:51,080
is being shown in the paper,
which is a way to interpret what

81
00:04:51,080 --> 00:04:52,540
each of these heads do.

82
00:04:52,540 --> 00:04:59,690
So we have this concept called
attention map, which basically

83
00:04:59,690 --> 00:05:08,490
tries to represent the value
of each of these query,

84
00:05:08,490 --> 00:05:10,930
dot product query.

85
00:05:10,930 --> 00:05:14,410
So in this example,
what we're interested in

86
00:05:14,410 --> 00:05:23,210
is to see which other token is
being most similar to token its.

87
00:05:23,210 --> 00:05:29,490
And so what we do is we take
a look at the quantities,

88
00:05:29,490 --> 00:05:33,650
the query that is
representing its,

89
00:05:33,650 --> 00:05:37,650
dot product, all other keys.

90
00:05:37,650 --> 00:05:41,610
And we look at what
are the keys are

91
00:05:41,610 --> 00:05:47,010
leading to a high value of the
dot product query times key.

92
00:05:47,010 --> 00:05:49,450
And when you do that,
basically what you see

93
00:05:49,450 --> 00:05:53,050
or what the paper sees is
you have these two words, so

94
00:05:53,050 --> 00:05:57,090
application and law, which
are highlighted as being

95
00:05:57,090 --> 00:05:58,990
with the high-attention weight.

96
00:05:58,990 --> 00:06:01,490
So attention weight
here being the dot

97
00:06:01,490 --> 00:06:07,090
product of the query
its, and the key for each

98
00:06:07,090 --> 00:06:08,530
of these tokens.

99
00:06:08,530 --> 00:06:13,690
And I guess there is also
a way to interpret those.

100
00:06:13,690 --> 00:06:15,730
And here you can see
that the tokens that

101
00:06:15,730 --> 00:06:21,170
are being highlighted are
law and application, which

102
00:06:21,170 --> 00:06:24,570
basically makes sense
because the token its

103
00:06:24,570 --> 00:06:28,330
is referring to law.

104
00:06:28,330 --> 00:06:31,610
So basically, the
model needs to learn

105
00:06:31,610 --> 00:06:35,970
how to associate these words
with what happened before.

106
00:06:35,970 --> 00:06:39,350
And its is also
referring to application,

107
00:06:39,350 --> 00:06:42,810
which is also another way of
explaining why that is the case.

108
00:06:42,810 --> 00:06:45,490
And so here what the
authors chose to do

109
00:06:45,490 --> 00:06:50,050
was to show these
values as a function

110
00:06:50,050 --> 00:06:52,690
of these different heads.

111
00:06:52,690 --> 00:06:54,830
So for instance,
on the left side,

112
00:06:54,830 --> 00:06:58,970
these are the
intensity for heads,

113
00:06:58,970 --> 00:07:00,770
for let's say the first heads.

114
00:07:00,770 --> 00:07:04,050
And then the second heads
shows that the intensity

115
00:07:04,050 --> 00:07:05,250
is very high for law.

116
00:07:05,250 --> 00:07:10,930
So basically, long story
short, these heads may learn,

117
00:07:10,930 --> 00:07:17,750
I guess, different ways of
figuring out what words matters.

118
00:07:17,750 --> 00:07:18,250
Yeah.

119
00:07:30,165 --> 00:07:30,790
Great question.

120
00:07:30,790 --> 00:07:33,750
So the question is, when we're
doing all these computations,

121
00:07:33,750 --> 00:07:37,470
are they going through
different MLPs.

122
00:07:37,470 --> 00:07:42,970
The answer is that we're going
to have different projection

123
00:07:42,970 --> 00:07:44,670
matrices for each of them.

124
00:07:48,690 --> 00:07:53,130
So we had this detailed example
that actually went through that

125
00:07:53,130 --> 00:07:58,010
where each head is going
to have its own projection.

126
00:07:58,010 --> 00:08:01,090
And in parallel, you're going
to have that computation that's

127
00:08:01,090 --> 00:08:03,170
going to happen.

128
00:08:03,170 --> 00:08:08,330
So each head is going to have
one result here, that is then

129
00:08:08,330 --> 00:08:13,850
going to be concatenated and
then projected once again when

130
00:08:13,850 --> 00:08:16,890
the output matrix.

131
00:08:16,890 --> 00:08:20,930
So yeah, long story short,
it's highly parallelized.

132
00:08:20,930 --> 00:08:24,150
And it's basically
just like projections.

133
00:08:24,150 --> 00:08:29,330
And here you have some matrix
multiplication and softmax.

134
00:08:29,330 --> 00:08:30,610
Does that make sense?

135
00:08:30,610 --> 00:08:32,870
Cool.

136
00:08:32,870 --> 00:08:34,190
Any other questions on this?

137
00:08:38,289 --> 00:08:38,789
