153
00:09:25,210 --> 00:09:28,850
So with that, we're going to
start the actual meat of what

154
00:09:28,850 --> 00:09:31,730
we're going to discuss today.

155
00:09:31,730 --> 00:09:35,810
So surprisingly, this
transformer architecture,

156
00:09:35,810 --> 00:09:39,090
which was introduced
in 2017, is actually

157
00:09:39,090 --> 00:09:47,370
an architecture that has still
stayed relevant along the years.

158
00:09:47,370 --> 00:09:52,490
And there are a few components
that have slightly changed.

159
00:09:52,490 --> 00:09:54,730
And we're going to see
which ones they are.

160
00:09:54,730 --> 00:09:57,370
So there are some
slight variations.

161
00:09:57,370 --> 00:10:00,850
But overall, today's
models are, we're

162
00:10:00,850 --> 00:10:05,650
going to see, all more or less
based on the initial transformer

163
00:10:05,650 --> 00:10:07,570
architecture.

164
00:10:07,570 --> 00:10:11,330
So we're going to try to
divide the class in two parts.

165
00:10:11,330 --> 00:10:13,650
So the first one is
what I'm going to cover,

166
00:10:13,650 --> 00:10:17,050
which is what are the parts
of the transformer that

167
00:10:17,050 --> 00:10:20,530
are important and that
had some variation.

168
00:10:20,530 --> 00:10:25,150
And in the second part, Shervine
is going to talk about, I guess,

169
00:10:25,150 --> 00:10:27,970
the nomenclature
of today's models

170
00:10:27,970 --> 00:10:32,890
and how they relate to
the original transformer.

171
00:10:32,890 --> 00:10:34,410
Cool.

172
00:10:34,410 --> 00:10:38,490
OK, so let's start with the
first important concept that's

173
00:10:38,490 --> 00:10:39,810
in this architecture.

174
00:10:39,810 --> 00:10:44,930
And this is the
position embedding.

175
00:10:44,930 --> 00:10:50,570
So if you remember, here
we're letting tokens interact

176
00:10:50,570 --> 00:10:54,030
with all other tokens
in a direct fashion.

177
00:10:54,030 --> 00:10:57,130
So they have direct links.

178
00:10:57,130 --> 00:11:00,810
But contrary to
things like RNNs,

179
00:11:00,810 --> 00:11:03,850
where you have a
sequential dependency where

180
00:11:03,850 --> 00:11:07,410
you process each
token one at a time,

181
00:11:07,410 --> 00:11:13,170
here you're basically losing
this idea of a token being

182
00:11:13,170 --> 00:11:15,690
processed before another one.

183
00:11:15,690 --> 00:11:21,090
So you lose this
position information.

184
00:11:21,090 --> 00:11:29,970
So as a result of that, we
need to somehow quantify tokens

185
00:11:29,970 --> 00:11:35,090
at each position and try to
inject that information when

186
00:11:35,090 --> 00:11:40,130
the transformer is
processing the inputs.

187
00:11:40,130 --> 00:11:42,370
So how are we going to do that?

188
00:11:42,370 --> 00:11:46,930
So the original
transformer paper authors,

189
00:11:46,930 --> 00:11:52,450
they chose to have a
dedicated embedding.

190
00:11:52,450 --> 00:11:57,050
And when I say dedicated, what
that means is each position

191
00:11:57,050 --> 00:11:59,370
has one embedding.

192
00:11:59,370 --> 00:12:01,770
So position 1 has one
embedding, position 2

193
00:12:01,770 --> 00:12:04,410
has one embedding,
et cetera, et cetera.

194
00:12:04,410 --> 00:12:10,850
And what they chose to do
is to add that embedding

195
00:12:10,850 --> 00:12:14,050
to the input-token embedding.

196
00:12:14,050 --> 00:12:18,290
So for instance, if I say a
cute teddy bear is reading,

197
00:12:18,290 --> 00:12:24,690
which is position
number 1, representing

198
00:12:24,690 --> 00:12:33,390
the token a, plus the embedding
representing the first position.

199
00:12:33,390 --> 00:12:33,890
Yeah.

200
00:12:39,290 --> 00:12:40,270
It's a great question.

201
00:12:40,270 --> 00:12:42,610
So the question is, are
the position embeddings

202
00:12:42,610 --> 00:12:44,810
learned or static?

203
00:12:44,810 --> 00:12:50,210
Both, as in the authors
have tried both.

204
00:12:50,210 --> 00:12:52,270
And we're going to see
what the second one is.

205
00:12:52,270 --> 00:12:57,850
But I guess here let's
suppose that they are learned.

206
00:12:57,850 --> 00:12:58,910
So what does that mean?

207
00:12:58,910 --> 00:13:03,410
So that means that
basically you need to learn

208
00:13:03,410 --> 00:13:06,810
embeddings for each position.

209
00:13:06,810 --> 00:13:10,810
And the problem
with this approach

210
00:13:10,810 --> 00:13:13,810
is that you're very
much dependent on what

211
00:13:13,810 --> 00:13:16,210
is in your training set.

212
00:13:16,210 --> 00:13:20,650
So for instance, like here,
if you have somehow a text

213
00:13:20,650 --> 00:13:23,570
that always has something that
is happening at position number

214
00:13:23,570 --> 00:13:30,490
2, your learned embeddings will
have that bias kind of learned.

215
00:13:30,490 --> 00:13:33,810
So that's one
limitation of that.

216
00:13:33,810 --> 00:13:39,890
Second limitation is you
can only learn positions up

217
00:13:39,890 --> 00:13:44,460
to the max number of position
that is in your training set.

218
00:13:44,460 --> 00:13:47,260
So let's suppose you train
your transformer on sequences

219
00:13:47,260 --> 00:13:51,820
that are up to, let's
say, 512, let's say.

220
00:13:51,820 --> 00:13:56,080
You can only learn position
embeddings up to that position.

221
00:13:56,080 --> 00:13:56,580
Right?

222
00:14:06,080 --> 00:14:07,300
Yeah.

223
00:14:07,300 --> 00:14:10,160
So the question is, I guess,
how do you parameterize that?

224
00:14:10,160 --> 00:14:12,700
So I guess what
you do is you have

225
00:14:12,700 --> 00:14:17,260
a placeholder of a learnable
position embedding,

226
00:14:17,260 --> 00:14:20,740
let's say between
position 1 and 512.

227
00:14:20,740 --> 00:14:24,100
And basically, when
you do your training,

228
00:14:24,100 --> 00:14:26,900
you're just letting
these weights

229
00:14:26,900 --> 00:14:29,740
be learned through
the regular gradient

230
00:14:29,740 --> 00:14:33,180
descent, all these things.

231
00:14:33,180 --> 00:14:35,460
So yeah, so this is
like the first method.

232
00:14:35,460 --> 00:14:39,260
But as I was mentioning,
it has its limitations,

233
00:14:39,260 --> 00:14:43,020
because you can only learn
embeddings of positions

234
00:14:43,020 --> 00:14:48,260
up to the max position that is
present in the training set.

235
00:14:48,260 --> 00:14:51,260
So for instance, if you
have at inference time

236
00:14:51,260 --> 00:14:54,260
a position that is
beyond the position that

237
00:14:54,260 --> 00:14:58,560
was in the training set, well,
you have not learned that.

238
00:14:58,560 --> 00:15:02,380
So you need to find a
way to infer the value.

239
00:15:02,380 --> 00:15:06,166
So that's the second limitation.

240
00:15:06,166 --> 00:15:09,220
But yeah, but on the pro
side, I guess you're just

241
00:15:09,220 --> 00:15:11,420
letting your model learn.

242
00:15:11,420 --> 00:15:13,900
And we've seen that
the gradient descent

243
00:15:13,900 --> 00:15:19,060
does wonders when it comes to
just learning from the data.

244
00:15:19,060 --> 00:15:19,720
So yeah.

245
00:15:19,720 --> 00:15:23,820
And for these
reasons, these methods

246
00:15:23,820 --> 00:15:29,260
was something that the authors
said that was performing well,

247
00:15:29,260 --> 00:15:34,380
along with the second
method, which is different,

248
00:15:34,380 --> 00:15:38,700
which is around
having an arbitrary

249
00:15:38,700 --> 00:15:44,460
formula for each
dimension corresponding

250
00:15:44,460 --> 00:15:46,100
to a position embedding.

251
00:15:46,100 --> 00:15:48,380
And we're going to see that now.

252
00:15:48,380 --> 00:15:54,260
So first method was you have
one embedding per position,

253
00:15:54,260 --> 00:15:56,860
and you just learn that.

254
00:15:56,860 --> 00:16:01,300
Second method is you have
one embedding per position,

255
00:16:01,300 --> 00:16:02,920
but you're not
going to learn that.

256
00:16:02,920 --> 00:16:05,500
You're going to have something
that is predetermined

257
00:16:05,500 --> 00:16:08,140
that you're going to use.

258
00:16:08,140 --> 00:16:12,620
And we're going to see that
what the authors choose

259
00:16:12,620 --> 00:16:18,300
was a formulation
using sine and cosine.

260
00:16:18,300 --> 00:16:22,600
So it can feel weird,
why did they choose this.

261
00:16:22,600 --> 00:16:24,620
But we're going to see
why that makes sense.

262
00:16:24,620 --> 00:16:32,100
So the idea here is for a
given position, let's say m,

263
00:16:32,100 --> 00:16:36,420
have a vector of size d model.

264
00:16:36,420 --> 00:16:38,857
So d needs to
match the dimension

265
00:16:38,857 --> 00:16:40,940
of your token embeddings,
because of course you're

266
00:16:40,940 --> 00:16:42,860
adding them.

267
00:16:42,860 --> 00:16:48,220
And what you're going to
do is, for every index

268
00:16:48,220 --> 00:16:52,180
you're going to compute the
corresponding value with respect

269
00:16:52,180 --> 00:16:54,780
to these formulas.

270
00:16:54,780 --> 00:16:56,040
So what are these formulas?

271
00:16:56,040 --> 00:17:02,500
So it's basically sine
of something times m.

272
00:17:02,500 --> 00:17:05,180
And we're going to see
what that something means.

273
00:17:05,180 --> 00:17:11,380
And then the second one is
cosine of something times m.

274
00:17:11,380 --> 00:17:14,009
So who remembers
trigonometry formulas?

275
00:17:17,640 --> 00:17:18,140
Cool.

276
00:17:18,140 --> 00:17:19,619
Everyone.

277
00:17:19,619 --> 00:17:24,720
So before we go into that, let's
just simplify the notations.

278
00:17:24,720 --> 00:17:27,940
Let's just assume that this
big quantity that you saw

279
00:17:27,940 --> 00:17:29,740
is actually
something like omega.

280
00:17:29,740 --> 00:17:35,140
So let's suppose it's omega
as a function of i times m.

281
00:17:35,140 --> 00:17:38,320
And you note omega i
as being this quantity,

282
00:17:38,320 --> 00:17:44,580
so 10,000 to the power
of minus 2i over d model.

283
00:17:44,580 --> 00:17:50,780
Let's suppose you construct your
embeddings to have this way.

284
00:17:50,780 --> 00:17:57,580
Then, I guess I want us to think
about why that would make sense.

285
00:17:57,580 --> 00:18:01,220
Because if you think
about it, what you want

286
00:18:01,220 --> 00:18:06,700
is to represent
positions in a way

287
00:18:06,700 --> 00:18:10,300
that reflects the
following fact--

288
00:18:10,300 --> 00:18:13,340
words that are
close together are

289
00:18:13,340 --> 00:18:16,900
likely to be more relevant,
as opposed to words

290
00:18:16,900 --> 00:18:19,040
that are further together.

291
00:18:19,040 --> 00:18:24,180
So if you have two words that
are like just one position apart

292
00:18:24,180 --> 00:18:28,940
versus 10,000 position apart,
what you want is that the one

293
00:18:28,940 --> 00:18:34,900
that is one position apart is
more similar than the other one.

294
00:18:34,900 --> 00:18:36,980
So let's see if the
formula makes sense.

295
00:18:36,980 --> 00:18:41,540
So let's suppose you have two
position embeddings, so one

296
00:18:41,540 --> 00:18:46,900
at position m and the
other one at position n.

297
00:18:46,900 --> 00:18:48,980
And let's suppose you
compute in all the values

298
00:18:48,980 --> 00:18:54,420
from this predetermined formula.

299
00:18:54,420 --> 00:18:59,340
Well, it turns out,
if you remember

300
00:18:59,340 --> 00:19:05,860
your trigonometry formulas,
so cosine of a minus b

301
00:19:05,860 --> 00:19:12,540
is equal to cosine of a cosine
of b, plus sine a sine b.

302
00:19:12,540 --> 00:19:14,790
Right?

303
00:19:14,790 --> 00:19:21,780
Well, turns out that if you
express cosine of omega i,

304
00:19:21,780 --> 00:19:26,260
factor of m minus n, this is
something that you obtain.

305
00:19:26,260 --> 00:19:29,780
It's just the identity
that I mentioned.

306
00:19:29,780 --> 00:19:33,980
Well, it just turns
out that this quantity

307
00:19:33,980 --> 00:19:38,060
is just one component
that appears

308
00:19:38,060 --> 00:19:43,360
when you do the dot product of
these two position embeddings.

309
00:19:43,360 --> 00:19:43,860
Right?

310
00:19:43,860 --> 00:19:47,260
Because basically
here, when you do

311
00:19:47,260 --> 00:19:50,020
the dot product of position
m and position n, what you do

312
00:19:50,020 --> 00:19:53,640
is you take the first
position, you multiply them,

313
00:19:53,640 --> 00:19:55,160
then you plus the
second position,

314
00:19:55,160 --> 00:19:57,260
you multiply them,
et cetera, et cetera.

315
00:19:57,260 --> 00:20:02,720
And then you come here, it's
sign of this times sine of this,

316
00:20:02,720 --> 00:20:06,495
plus cosine of this
times cosine of this,

317
00:20:06,495 --> 00:20:11,060
which is just this quantity.

318
00:20:11,060 --> 00:20:14,660
So at the end of the
day, what you realize

319
00:20:14,660 --> 00:20:19,500
is that when you perform a dot
product of these embeddings,

320
00:20:19,500 --> 00:20:24,660
you end up with a
sum of cosine that

321
00:20:24,660 --> 00:20:29,480
are a function of the relative
distance between m and n.

322
00:20:32,480 --> 00:20:32,980
Yep.

323
00:20:42,780 --> 00:20:44,360
What do you mean by
pair, by the way?

324
00:21:01,700 --> 00:21:03,160
Exactly, yeah.

325
00:21:03,160 --> 00:21:06,117
So the question is, so
the closer they are,

326
00:21:06,117 --> 00:21:07,200
the more similar they are.

327
00:21:07,200 --> 00:21:09,500
So that's the intuition,
that basically

328
00:21:09,500 --> 00:21:13,340
this way of formulating
the embeddings

329
00:21:13,340 --> 00:21:18,220
is trying to approximate
or it's trying to mimic.

330
00:21:18,220 --> 00:21:22,260
So with that, you basically
obtain a dot product

331
00:21:22,260 --> 00:21:25,380
that is just a function of m
and n, the relative distance

332
00:21:25,380 --> 00:21:27,820
between them, actually.

333
00:21:27,820 --> 00:21:31,740
And just as a reminder, so why
do I care about the dot product?

334
00:21:31,740 --> 00:21:35,980
Because if you remember,
in the embedding world

335
00:21:35,980 --> 00:21:38,940
when we try to quantify
the similarity between two

336
00:21:38,940 --> 00:21:41,380
embeddings, what
we do is typically

337
00:21:41,380 --> 00:21:45,220
something that is involving
the dot product of these two.

338
00:21:45,220 --> 00:21:48,100
So you typically have
the cosine similarity.

339
00:21:48,100 --> 00:21:51,100
The cosine similarity
is just dot product

340
00:21:51,100 --> 00:21:53,680
over the norm of each embedding.

341
00:21:53,680 --> 00:21:56,940
So which is basically
a dot product.

342
00:21:56,940 --> 00:21:57,620
Right?

343
00:21:57,620 --> 00:22:00,280
So that's why we care
about the dot product.

344
00:22:00,280 --> 00:22:02,740
And here we see,
great, it's a function

345
00:22:02,740 --> 00:22:06,460
of the relative distance
between the two.

346
00:22:06,460 --> 00:22:10,500
So in particular,
again, if you remember

347
00:22:10,500 --> 00:22:19,540
your trigonometry
class, cosine of 0 is 1.

348
00:22:19,540 --> 00:22:24,500
And the higher this
number, the lower the value

349
00:22:24,500 --> 00:22:27,245
of cosine of this number.

350
00:22:27,245 --> 00:22:30,710
Of course, it's periodic,
so what I'm saying

351
00:22:30,710 --> 00:22:31,970
is not necessarily true.

352
00:22:31,970 --> 00:22:38,630
Past pi, just goes
the other way.

353
00:22:38,630 --> 00:22:44,230
But I guess what I'm trying
to say is for m equal to n,

354
00:22:44,230 --> 00:22:49,870
you have basically a
sum of cosine of 0.

355
00:22:49,870 --> 00:22:57,430
And it is the value at which
this quantity is maximum.

356
00:22:57,430 --> 00:23:01,290
So when m is equal to n,
this quantity is maximum.

357
00:23:01,290 --> 00:23:05,270
Which means basically if you're
looking at the position itself,

358
00:23:05,270 --> 00:23:07,190
it's the most similar.

359
00:23:07,190 --> 00:23:10,310
Basically, it matches
our intuition.

360
00:23:10,310 --> 00:23:17,230
And so now when you plot the
values of the embeddings,

361
00:23:17,230 --> 00:23:18,690
this is what you obtain.

362
00:23:18,690 --> 00:23:22,570
So here in this
graph on the y-axis,

363
00:23:22,570 --> 00:23:24,910
I'm basically representing
all the embeddings

364
00:23:24,910 --> 00:23:29,710
for each of the, let's
say, 50 positions.

365
00:23:29,710 --> 00:23:33,630
And on the x-axis,
it's basically

366
00:23:33,630 --> 00:23:38,310
values along a given vector
across several dimensions

367
00:23:38,310 --> 00:23:39,670
of a vector.

368
00:23:39,670 --> 00:23:41,570
So if you take, let's
say, the first row,

369
00:23:41,570 --> 00:23:45,250
you're looking at the
first or number 0 position,

370
00:23:45,250 --> 00:23:48,430
depending on how you
index your vector.

371
00:23:48,430 --> 00:23:53,150
And you're looking at all
the values of the position 0

372
00:23:53,150 --> 00:23:55,750
embedding.

373
00:23:55,750 --> 00:24:02,350
And so you see that
for low dimensions,

374
00:24:02,350 --> 00:24:07,650
this value goes up and
down very frequently.

375
00:24:07,650 --> 00:24:10,430
So it's more high frequency.

376
00:24:10,430 --> 00:24:14,630
And when the dimension
is high, it basically

377
00:24:14,630 --> 00:24:18,250
takes a lot of time for the
value to go up and down.

378
00:24:18,250 --> 00:24:22,470
So it's basically
more low frequency.

379
00:24:22,470 --> 00:24:28,110
So this relates to this omega i
that I mentioned, this omega i.

380
00:24:28,110 --> 00:24:36,130
So omega i is very high
for low values of i,

381
00:24:36,130 --> 00:24:37,910
which is the dimension.

382
00:24:37,910 --> 00:24:43,390
And it's very low
for high values of i.

383
00:24:43,390 --> 00:24:45,510
So this basically
just determines

384
00:24:45,510 --> 00:24:49,020
how quickly your cosine
and sine basically vary.

385
00:24:52,150 --> 00:24:53,890
Cool.

386
00:24:53,890 --> 00:24:58,410
So this is what the
original authors have tried.

387
00:24:58,410 --> 00:25:00,910
And basically what
they said, what they

388
00:25:00,910 --> 00:25:05,350
noted was that
using these methods

389
00:25:05,350 --> 00:25:10,030
leads to comparable results
compared to the learned one.

390
00:25:10,030 --> 00:25:12,270
But here we have
a big advantage,

391
00:25:12,270 --> 00:25:15,950
because it can extend to any
sequence length, not just

392
00:25:15,950 --> 00:25:19,470
a sequence length that
you saw at training time.

393
00:25:19,470 --> 00:25:22,590
And this is one of the
reasons why this may be

394
00:25:22,590 --> 00:25:23,930
something that is preferable.

395
00:25:26,470 --> 00:25:28,430
So yeah, this is the
intuition and this

396
00:25:28,430 --> 00:25:30,790
is what the authors chose.

397
00:25:30,790 --> 00:25:32,970
Now, fast forward to 2025.

398
00:25:32,970 --> 00:25:36,550
I guess you may ask me,
are we still using that?

399
00:25:36,550 --> 00:25:39,250
And the answer is kind of.

400
00:25:39,250 --> 00:25:44,110
So we're still using this
idea of we want far--

401
00:25:44,110 --> 00:25:49,430
I guess, tokens to be less
similar than closer tokens.

402
00:25:49,430 --> 00:25:53,690
But we're not injecting the
embedding like they did.

403
00:25:53,690 --> 00:25:56,630
And we're going to see why.

404
00:25:56,630 --> 00:26:00,830
Because if you remember,
what you care about

405
00:26:00,830 --> 00:26:05,350
is determining
how similar tokens

406
00:26:05,350 --> 00:26:10,790
are in the self-attention
computation.

407
00:26:10,790 --> 00:26:12,790
And where does the
self-attention computation

408
00:26:12,790 --> 00:26:14,670
happen?

409
00:26:14,670 --> 00:26:17,750
In the attention layer.

410
00:26:17,750 --> 00:26:19,950
But here, what did I say?

411
00:26:19,950 --> 00:26:22,830
I said, let's compute
these embeddings

412
00:26:22,830 --> 00:26:25,630
and let's add them here.

413
00:26:25,630 --> 00:26:30,110
But actually what we want is
to reflect this similarity

414
00:26:30,110 --> 00:26:32,650
in the attention layer.

415
00:26:35,270 --> 00:26:36,330
Do you have a question?

416
00:26:36,330 --> 00:26:36,830
Yeah.

417
00:26:40,790 --> 00:26:42,402
So in this first method, yes.

418
00:26:42,402 --> 00:26:44,610
So the question is, is it
added to the input feature.

419
00:26:44,610 --> 00:26:45,110
Yes.

420
00:26:47,692 --> 00:26:48,710
Yes, just add.

421
00:26:48,710 --> 00:26:50,110
Yeah, yeah.

422
00:26:50,110 --> 00:26:55,670
But the problem is,
we mostly want these,

423
00:26:55,670 --> 00:27:02,230
I guess, intuition to hold true
in the multi-head attention

424
00:27:02,230 --> 00:27:03,910
layer.

425
00:27:03,910 --> 00:27:07,110
So this is one of
the reasons why

426
00:27:07,110 --> 00:27:12,390
people have tried different
variations, and in particular

427
00:27:12,390 --> 00:27:17,590
have these position
embeddings intervene directly

428
00:27:17,590 --> 00:27:22,230
in the attention layer,
as opposed to the input.

429
00:27:22,230 --> 00:27:24,990
Because basically when
you do it at the input--

430
00:27:24,990 --> 00:27:26,650
just here, fair, OK--

431
00:27:26,650 --> 00:27:28,750
it's going to be
roughly something that

432
00:27:28,750 --> 00:27:31,050
is going to go into
this attention layer,

433
00:27:31,050 --> 00:27:33,710
but it's kind of indirect.

434
00:27:33,710 --> 00:27:41,390
So what we want is to directly
do something about the attention

435
00:27:41,390 --> 00:27:45,030
formula that would,
I guess, reflect

436
00:27:45,030 --> 00:27:48,830
the fact that we want close
tokens to be more similar,

437
00:27:48,830 --> 00:27:52,590
compared to further tokens.

438
00:27:52,590 --> 00:27:56,550
And the way we do that
is, if you remember,

439
00:27:56,550 --> 00:28:02,350
the self-attention layer is
basically the softmax of qk

440
00:28:02,350 --> 00:28:06,870
transpose over square
root of d times v.

441
00:28:06,870 --> 00:28:10,470
So what we want is to
add a little something

442
00:28:10,470 --> 00:28:13,670
inside that softmax,
which is basically

443
00:28:13,670 --> 00:28:18,990
where you quantify how similar
a token is to another token.

444
00:28:18,990 --> 00:28:21,870
You want to add a
little something

445
00:28:21,870 --> 00:28:26,110
to reflect the fact
that some tokens,

446
00:28:26,110 --> 00:28:28,790
they're supposed to be more
similar compared to that token,

447
00:28:28,790 --> 00:28:32,350
compared to others.

448
00:28:32,350 --> 00:28:37,350
So there's a few
methods that have tried

449
00:28:37,350 --> 00:28:41,190
to have some variation of that.

450
00:28:41,190 --> 00:28:48,390
So for those of us who know
the T5 paper, what we're

451
00:28:48,390 --> 00:28:51,830
going to see a little
bit later, they

452
00:28:51,830 --> 00:28:57,190
have tried these
relative position bias

453
00:28:57,190 --> 00:29:04,030
by learning the bias term,
which is in the formula above.

454
00:29:04,030 --> 00:29:08,310
So what they did
was, let's suppose

455
00:29:08,310 --> 00:29:13,470
you have a given distance
between the positions m and n.

456
00:29:13,470 --> 00:29:17,790
So their idea was,
let's learn that.

457
00:29:17,790 --> 00:29:24,150
Let's basically bucketize all
m minus n into some buckets.

458
00:29:24,150 --> 00:29:27,470
And let's just have
the model learn

459
00:29:27,470 --> 00:29:29,750
these quantities
that are then going

460
00:29:29,750 --> 00:29:31,120
to be injected into softmax.

461
00:29:34,050 --> 00:29:34,550
Yeah.

462
00:29:43,590 --> 00:29:45,790
So the question is,
does that pose a problem

463
00:29:45,790 --> 00:29:47,750
that the bias is
here with respect

464
00:29:47,750 --> 00:29:49,570
to the probability at the end?

465
00:29:49,570 --> 00:29:50,970
Because it has to sum to 1.

466
00:29:50,970 --> 00:29:54,030
Well, you can do whatever
you want inside the softmax,

467
00:29:54,030 --> 00:29:56,360
because the softmax is going
to normalize it anyways.

468
00:29:59,350 --> 00:30:02,870
So you can think of the bias as
being something that is maybe

469
00:30:02,870 --> 00:30:05,590
more negative for things
that are far apart, compared

470
00:30:05,590 --> 00:30:08,710
to things that are
closer together.

471
00:30:08,710 --> 00:30:13,910
So T5 says, let's learn them.

472
00:30:13,910 --> 00:30:19,430
We have another message from,
I guess, this "Train Short,

473
00:30:19,430 --> 00:30:22,870
Test Long" paper, which
introduced this method called

474
00:30:22,870 --> 00:30:24,190
ALiBi.

475
00:30:24,190 --> 00:30:30,110
ALiBi stands for Attention
with linear bias, I believe.

476
00:30:30,110 --> 00:30:33,550
And what they did
was, say instead

477
00:30:33,550 --> 00:30:37,510
of learning those
biases, let's actually

478
00:30:37,510 --> 00:30:40,270
have a deterministic
formula, which

479
00:30:40,270 --> 00:30:45,430
is as a function of the relative
difference between those two

480
00:30:45,430 --> 00:30:48,510
positions.

481
00:30:48,510 --> 00:30:49,490
And they said that.

482
00:30:49,490 --> 00:30:51,930
So they had some results.

483
00:30:51,930 --> 00:30:55,910
So all these papers, they always
compare based on one another

484
00:30:55,910 --> 00:31:01,230
to see which one is, I
guess, more performant.

485
00:31:01,230 --> 00:31:06,670
But the reality is is
that in today's models,

486
00:31:06,670 --> 00:31:14,550
most models actually use another
kind of position embedding

487
00:31:14,550 --> 00:31:16,110
method.

488
00:31:16,110 --> 00:31:18,910
And we're going to see it now.

489
00:31:18,910 --> 00:31:24,270
So this method
relies on rotating

490
00:31:24,270 --> 00:31:30,870
the query and the key
vector by some angle.

491
00:31:30,870 --> 00:31:34,370
And I guess you can think of
it as, you have your query,

492
00:31:34,370 --> 00:31:37,310
you have your key, let's
suppose in a 2D space.

493
00:31:37,310 --> 00:31:41,630
So what you're going to
do is rotate your query

494
00:31:41,630 --> 00:31:45,910
by some angle that is a
function of its position.

495
00:31:45,910 --> 00:31:53,110
And you're going to rotate the
key vector by some angle that is

496
00:31:53,110 --> 00:31:56,830
a function of its position n.

497
00:31:56,830 --> 00:32:01,010
And I guess how do you
do that, by the way?

498
00:32:01,010 --> 00:32:03,090
I wasn't supposed
to show this thing.

499
00:32:03,090 --> 00:32:06,150
So let's suppose you have
a vector, by the way.

500
00:32:06,150 --> 00:32:08,347
And you want to
rotate that vector,

501
00:32:08,347 --> 00:32:09,930
because I had the
answer on the slide.

502
00:32:09,930 --> 00:32:12,840
But how would you go
about this, I guess,

503
00:32:12,840 --> 00:32:18,380
for people who just want to
talk about this with intuition?

504
00:32:21,960 --> 00:32:28,700
So who here has done, I don't
know, rotations in space?

505
00:32:28,700 --> 00:32:29,200
Yeah.

506
00:32:33,560 --> 00:32:35,000
That's correct, yeah.

507
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:36,580
Matrix multiplication.

508
00:32:36,580 --> 00:32:38,520
And you're going to
use a quantity that's

509
00:32:38,520 --> 00:32:41,920
called rotation matrix.

510
00:32:41,920 --> 00:32:46,260
And the rotation matrix
is expressed as follows.

511
00:32:46,260 --> 00:32:51,240
So it's basically a 2 by 2
matrix in the 2D plane that has

512
00:32:51,240 --> 00:32:54,700
cosine of this angle,
minus sine of this angle,

513
00:32:54,700 --> 00:32:56,660
sine of this angle,
cosine of this angle.

514
00:32:56,660 --> 00:32:59,080
I'm looking at the time.

515
00:32:59,080 --> 00:33:02,800
It's quite simple to
just show that it works,

516
00:33:02,800 --> 00:33:04,840
but we may run out of time.

517
00:33:04,840 --> 00:33:06,360
Do you want me to
quickly show you

518
00:33:06,360 --> 00:33:12,160
that it's indeed a way
to rotate the vector?

519
00:33:12,160 --> 00:33:14,525
OK.

520
00:33:14,525 --> 00:33:19,720
So here as a reminder what we're
trying to show is that we can

521
00:33:19,720 --> 00:33:25,840
use a matrix multiplication to
rotate a vector in 2D space.

522
00:33:25,840 --> 00:33:29,120
So let's suppose we have
the following vector.

523
00:33:29,120 --> 00:33:38,640
That is something that you can
quantify with two dimensions,

524
00:33:38,640 --> 00:33:42,800
let's say x and y.

525
00:33:42,800 --> 00:33:45,600
You can express your vector
in 2D space with this.

526
00:33:45,600 --> 00:33:47,680
Right?

527
00:33:47,680 --> 00:33:57,320
But I guess this, if you note,
are the norm of the vector,

528
00:33:57,320 --> 00:34:05,400
and phi, the angle with
respect to the x-axis.

529
00:34:05,400 --> 00:34:16,440
You can also write v
as R with vector cosine

530
00:34:16,440 --> 00:34:18,860
of phi and sine of phi.

531
00:34:21,920 --> 00:34:24,215
Right?

532
00:34:24,215 --> 00:34:27,800
So if you multiply
the rotation matrix

533
00:34:27,800 --> 00:34:31,120
with this phi, what
you're going to obtain

534
00:34:31,120 --> 00:34:37,520
is some multiplication of cosine
minus sine, sine and cosine

535
00:34:37,520 --> 00:34:40,560
of this and that.

536
00:34:40,560 --> 00:34:42,900
And I will leave this
exercise for you.

537
00:34:42,900 --> 00:34:53,199
But you can show that
rotation times this v

538
00:34:53,199 --> 00:35:02,760
can be expressed as R of
cosine of theta plus phi,

539
00:35:02,760 --> 00:35:06,500
and sine of theta plus phi.

540
00:35:09,640 --> 00:35:10,860
So this is a quick proof.

541
00:35:10,860 --> 00:35:14,960
So I'll just leave you the
multiplication of the rotation

542
00:35:14,960 --> 00:35:17,880
matrix and v. But
you will obtain

543
00:35:17,880 --> 00:35:24,120
these trigonometric
identities that will, I guess,

544
00:35:24,120 --> 00:35:26,200
lead you to this formula.

545
00:35:26,200 --> 00:35:28,600
This basically shows
that if you multiply

546
00:35:28,600 --> 00:35:33,400
this matrix and this vector,
you're basically rotating

547
00:35:33,400 --> 00:35:35,840
the vector by this angle.

548
00:35:35,840 --> 00:35:38,062
Yeah.

549
00:35:38,062 --> 00:35:40,020
So the question is, why
do you want to do this?

550
00:35:40,020 --> 00:35:40,937
It's a great question.

551
00:35:40,937 --> 00:35:42,220
It's my next slide.

552
00:35:42,220 --> 00:35:45,800
So this is just a little intro.

553
00:35:45,800 --> 00:35:52,120
So I guess here, just going
back to this method, what

554
00:35:52,120 --> 00:35:58,480
we want to do is to quantify
the similarity between tokens,

555
00:35:58,480 --> 00:36:02,040
and have close tokens
be more similar compared

556
00:36:02,040 --> 00:36:06,080
to tokens that are more afar.

557
00:36:06,080 --> 00:36:12,160
So the problem that we had
with the previous methods was--

558
00:36:12,160 --> 00:36:16,420
so in the first method,
this learned embedding,

559
00:36:16,420 --> 00:36:18,800
you always had this
overfitting issue.

560
00:36:18,800 --> 00:36:21,480
Because basically when
you learn these biases,

561
00:36:21,480 --> 00:36:25,220
it always depends on which
training set you have.

562
00:36:25,220 --> 00:36:29,120
So maybe your data set is
in a way that, let's say,

563
00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:32,080
tokens that are close are
similar, but in a different way

564
00:36:32,080 --> 00:36:35,400
compared to what you
see at inference time.

565
00:36:35,400 --> 00:36:41,820
And this ALiBi method, it didn't
have that learnable component,

566
00:36:41,820 --> 00:36:44,280
but it was quite
restrictive, because it's

567
00:36:44,280 --> 00:36:48,040
a very simple formula after all,
just the relative difference

568
00:36:48,040 --> 00:36:49,320
between n and m.

569
00:36:49,320 --> 00:36:52,800
So I guess people have tried
different ways of coming up

570
00:36:52,800 --> 00:36:59,320
with something that tells you
that, I guess, an embedding that

571
00:36:59,320 --> 00:37:03,760
reflects the fact that you want
further positions to be less

572
00:37:03,760 --> 00:37:06,120
similar than closer ones.

573
00:37:06,120 --> 00:37:09,520
So in this method,
we're going back

574
00:37:09,520 --> 00:37:13,000
to the sine and
cosine world from what

575
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:14,960
the author had proposed.

576
00:37:14,960 --> 00:37:19,160
And think about
similarity from the lens

577
00:37:19,160 --> 00:37:24,200
of cosine and sine functions.

578
00:37:24,200 --> 00:37:26,640
So this is a little intro.

579
00:37:26,640 --> 00:37:29,840
And their method is called RoPE.

580
00:37:29,840 --> 00:37:31,520
So I'm not sure if
you've heard of it.

581
00:37:31,520 --> 00:37:36,800
So it stands for Rotary
Position Embeddings.

582
00:37:36,800 --> 00:37:39,640
And we're going to see
that this method-- so

583
00:37:39,640 --> 00:37:41,340
why do we care
about this method?

584
00:37:41,340 --> 00:37:45,080
So this method has
two great things.

585
00:37:45,080 --> 00:37:53,120
So the first one is that if you
rotate the query and the key,

586
00:37:53,120 --> 00:37:55,640
you will end up
with a quantity that

587
00:37:55,640 --> 00:37:58,040
will be a function of
the relative distance

588
00:37:58,040 --> 00:37:59,813
between the two.

589
00:37:59,813 --> 00:38:01,480
That's going to be
very nice, and that's

590
00:38:01,480 --> 00:38:04,720
why I wrote this thing
on the blackboard.

591
00:38:04,720 --> 00:38:06,220
Not sure if you can
see, by the way,

592
00:38:06,220 --> 00:38:10,220
but we won't have time to go
into the mathematical detail.

593
00:38:10,220 --> 00:38:14,200
But if you want to just
express these things at home,

594
00:38:14,200 --> 00:38:16,380
this is just the foundation.

595
00:38:19,120 --> 00:38:26,160
And so in particular, if you
remember your attention formula,

596
00:38:26,160 --> 00:38:30,200
so you have query
times key transpose.

597
00:38:30,200 --> 00:38:35,240
So if you rotate the
query by an angle m

598
00:38:35,240 --> 00:38:40,920
and the key by an angle n,
what you're going to end up

599
00:38:40,920 --> 00:38:48,480
is a formula that has the
rotation matrix of angle theta

600
00:38:48,480 --> 00:38:53,040
and, I guess, n minus m.

601
00:38:53,040 --> 00:38:55,040
And this is great
because this is

602
00:38:55,040 --> 00:38:57,880
a function of the relative
distance between these two

603
00:38:57,880 --> 00:38:58,740
positions.

604
00:39:01,680 --> 00:39:03,900
OK, so why do I talk
about this in detail?

605
00:39:03,900 --> 00:39:06,440
Well, it turns out that
most models these days,

606
00:39:06,440 --> 00:39:12,120
they use RoPE, which
is why it's important.

607
00:39:12,120 --> 00:39:16,160
And I would say another thing,
it's maybe a little bit hard

608
00:39:16,160 --> 00:39:19,440
to get the intuition
as to why that works.

609
00:39:19,440 --> 00:39:23,800
But hopefully, the explanation
that I gave regarding the sine

610
00:39:23,800 --> 00:39:26,880
and cosine at the very
beginning can help you just

611
00:39:26,880 --> 00:39:30,000
build that intuition.

612
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:34,520
And speaking of
that, it turns out

613
00:39:34,520 --> 00:39:40,000
that the upper bound of
the attention weight given

614
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:44,920
by the query and the
key is such that we

615
00:39:44,920 --> 00:39:48,840
observe a long-term decay.

616
00:39:48,840 --> 00:39:53,600
Meaning that as n
minus m is large,

617
00:39:53,600 --> 00:39:58,440
we do see the upper bound
that gets smaller and smaller.

618
00:39:58,440 --> 00:40:02,600
Well, you see these
little oscillations,

619
00:40:02,600 --> 00:40:04,180
it's not perfect either.

620
00:40:04,180 --> 00:40:09,160
But we do have
some mathematical,

621
00:40:09,160 --> 00:40:13,520
I guess, results as to
just the upper bounds

622
00:40:13,520 --> 00:40:14,980
decaying over the long-term.

623
00:40:18,160 --> 00:40:19,800
Cool.

624
00:40:19,800 --> 00:40:21,800
Any questions on this?

625
00:40:21,800 --> 00:40:24,300
Yeah, yeah.

626
00:40:38,600 --> 00:40:39,380
Exactly, yeah.

627
00:40:39,380 --> 00:40:41,680
So the question is
the relative distance

628
00:40:41,680 --> 00:40:43,620
is captured in the
rotation matrix--

629
00:40:43,620 --> 00:40:46,090
and yes, yes.

630
00:40:49,520 --> 00:40:50,180
Oh, yeah.

631
00:40:53,383 --> 00:40:54,300
It's a great question.

632
00:40:54,300 --> 00:40:56,480
So the question
is, what is theta?

633
00:40:56,480 --> 00:40:58,320
So theta is actually fixed.

634
00:40:58,320 --> 00:41:01,870
So do you remember this omega
that I talked about here?

635
00:41:01,870 --> 00:41:03,600
Here.

636
00:41:03,600 --> 00:41:08,610
So it's basically some
function of i and d.

637
00:41:08,610 --> 00:41:12,050
I actually pass
it quite quickly.

638
00:41:12,050 --> 00:41:17,690
But what I showed you
is in the 2D space.

639
00:41:17,690 --> 00:41:20,670
But here we're in a
d-dimensional space,

640
00:41:20,670 --> 00:41:22,450
which is greater than 2.

641
00:41:22,450 --> 00:41:25,070
So I glossed it very quickly.

642
00:41:25,070 --> 00:41:30,290
But the way you extend this
method is by having these 2D

643
00:41:30,290 --> 00:41:32,170
space by block.

644
00:41:32,170 --> 00:41:36,810
But then the theta is a
function of typically something

645
00:41:36,810 --> 00:41:43,610
that you fix, but a function
of i, which is the dimension.

646
00:41:43,610 --> 00:41:48,210
It's basically between
1 and d over 2.

647
00:41:48,210 --> 00:41:52,890
It's a function of that, and
it's a function of d as well.

648
00:41:52,890 --> 00:41:57,990
You will see this theta as being
roughly equal to omega i, just

649
00:41:57,990 --> 00:42:00,870
this one, more or
less, more or less.

650
00:42:04,190 --> 00:42:04,690
Sorry?

651
00:42:07,970 --> 00:42:11,530
Oh, so the question is, so
that it has the same dimension

652
00:42:11,530 --> 00:42:13,270
as the latent dimension?

653
00:42:13,270 --> 00:42:21,090
So, well, here you have
a product of matrices.

654
00:42:21,090 --> 00:42:23,350
So you need to have
the dimensions match.

655
00:42:23,350 --> 00:42:24,690
So I guess your answer-- yeah.

656
00:42:30,345 --> 00:42:31,510
Does that make sense?

657
00:42:34,330 --> 00:42:35,850
I'll take that as a yes.

658
00:42:35,850 --> 00:42:37,730
So I spent a bunch
of time on this,

659
00:42:37,730 --> 00:42:41,490
because I think this is
actually quite important.

660
00:42:41,490 --> 00:42:43,370
A lot of models use this.

661
00:42:43,370 --> 00:42:47,610
And yeah, I guess the
intuition is not super obvious.

662
00:42:47,610 --> 00:42:51,210
So I hope this was helpful.

663
00:42:51,210 --> 00:42:54,010
So this was position embeddings.

664
00:42:54,010 --> 00:42:56,290
Yeah.

665
00:42:56,290 --> 00:42:59,370
Oh, yeah.

666
00:42:59,370 --> 00:43:03,130
Yeah, so the question is about,
how do you obtain this curve?

667
00:43:03,130 --> 00:43:05,610
So this is actually a
curve that I believe

668
00:43:05,610 --> 00:43:09,410
is shown mathematically.

669
00:43:09,410 --> 00:43:11,300
So it's kind of complicated.

670
00:43:11,300 --> 00:43:13,050
We're not going to
write down the formula.

671
00:43:13,050 --> 00:43:15,530
But if you're interested,
so in this paper,

672
00:43:15,530 --> 00:43:18,250
in the RoFormer paper,
there's an appendix

673
00:43:18,250 --> 00:43:20,690
where they show
mathematically that it is

674
00:43:20,690 --> 00:43:22,690
upper bounded by some quantity.

675
00:43:22,690 --> 00:43:25,610
And this is what
this is showing.

676
00:43:25,610 --> 00:43:27,020
Yeah, great question.

677
00:43:29,930 --> 00:43:30,910
Cool.

678
00:43:30,910 --> 00:43:34,130
So, position
embeddings is one part

679
00:43:34,130 --> 00:43:36,850
of the transformer that
has changed a little bit.

680
00:43:36,850 --> 00:43:40,490
And we've seen how
that changed, and why.

681
00:43:40,490 --> 00:43:42,930
So now we're going to
see another component

682
00:43:42,930 --> 00:43:47,810
of the transformer that has
also a little bit changed.

683
00:43:47,810 --> 00:43:52,330
And that component is
the layer normalization.

684
00:43:52,330 --> 00:43:56,450
So if you remember, the
transformer architecture,

685
00:43:56,450 --> 00:43:58,770
which is composed,
again, of encoder,

686
00:43:58,770 --> 00:44:02,730
decoder, and then you have
the components inside.

687
00:44:02,730 --> 00:44:08,410
So you have these boxes
that say add and norm.

688
00:44:08,410 --> 00:44:09,610
So what do they mean?

689
00:44:09,610 --> 00:44:17,410
So basically, here, what we do
is we take the input, as well as

690
00:44:17,410 --> 00:44:21,210
the output of this sublayer.

691
00:44:21,210 --> 00:44:27,530
We add them together,
and then we normalize.

692
00:44:27,530 --> 00:44:31,530
So this is a little trick
that the authors do.

693
00:44:31,530 --> 00:44:37,050
And it is shown in practice to
improve convergence and just

694
00:44:37,050 --> 00:44:40,010
make the convergence be quicker.

695
00:44:40,010 --> 00:44:42,890
So the idea is as follows--

696
00:44:42,890 --> 00:44:48,010
if you have a vector, sometimes
the components of the vector

697
00:44:48,010 --> 00:44:51,490
can be super large, sometimes
they can be super small.

698
00:44:51,490 --> 00:44:57,970
The idea here is to normalize
the components of your vector

699
00:44:57,970 --> 00:45:02,657
within some range,
some normalized range.

700
00:45:02,657 --> 00:45:04,490
So the way you're going
to do that is you're

701
00:45:04,490 --> 00:45:09,050
going to take your vector,
and then subtract it

702
00:45:09,050 --> 00:45:12,170
by the computed mean,
which is basically

703
00:45:12,170 --> 00:45:16,810
the sum of its components,
and normalize it by basically

704
00:45:16,810 --> 00:45:20,250
its standard deviation.

705
00:45:20,250 --> 00:45:22,610
And what you're
going to do is you're

706
00:45:22,610 --> 00:45:25,850
going to learn two quantities--

707
00:45:25,850 --> 00:45:30,410
one, gamma, which is going
to be the rescaling factor,

708
00:45:30,410 --> 00:45:38,130
and then beta, which is another
term as well that you learn.

709
00:45:38,130 --> 00:45:40,610
And you're going to let
these two quantities be

710
00:45:40,610 --> 00:45:43,810
learned by your model.

711
00:45:43,810 --> 00:45:46,690
And so in practice, as I
mentioned, so what this does

712
00:45:46,690 --> 00:45:50,250
is it helps with
training stability

713
00:45:50,250 --> 00:45:53,370
and with convergence time.

714
00:45:53,370 --> 00:45:57,370
So this was a technique that was
used in the original transformer

715
00:45:57,370 --> 00:45:59,650
paper.

716
00:45:59,650 --> 00:46:01,530
I just want to call
out that there has

717
00:46:01,530 --> 00:46:04,250
been some changes since then.

718
00:46:04,250 --> 00:46:08,650
So we went from
normalizing the input

719
00:46:08,650 --> 00:46:16,050
plus the output of the sublayer,
to having a sum of the input

720
00:46:16,050 --> 00:46:21,690
and the sublayer of
the normalized input.

721
00:46:21,690 --> 00:46:24,050
So in other words,
what we've done

722
00:46:24,050 --> 00:46:28,410
is to change where the
normalization is located.

723
00:46:28,410 --> 00:46:31,970
So here in the
transformer paper,

724
00:46:31,970 --> 00:46:36,890
it was what we now call
a post-norm version.

725
00:46:36,890 --> 00:46:40,210
And nowadays, we use
a pre-norm version,

726
00:46:40,210 --> 00:46:43,970
which basically consists of
having the LayerNorm right

727
00:46:43,970 --> 00:46:47,710
before the vector goes
into the sublayer.

728
00:46:47,710 --> 00:46:51,560
And sublayer here can be either
the attention layer or the FFN.

729
00:46:56,450 --> 00:47:00,210
But not only that, there
is also another change.

730
00:47:00,210 --> 00:47:04,090
So nowadays, people, they
do not use LayerNorm.

731
00:47:04,090 --> 00:47:07,170
They use something
else called RMSNorm--

732
00:47:07,170 --> 00:47:10,530
RMS, Root Mean
Square, Normalization,

733
00:47:10,530 --> 00:47:15,250
which is basically a variation
of what you've seen before.

734
00:47:15,250 --> 00:47:19,890
So instead of computing this,
basically what people do

735
00:47:19,890 --> 00:47:23,570
is they just normalize
x by the root

736
00:47:23,570 --> 00:47:29,890
mean square of the
components of x,

737
00:47:29,890 --> 00:47:34,050
and they learn
gamma, only gamma.

738
00:47:34,050 --> 00:47:35,350
So why do they do that?

739
00:47:35,350 --> 00:47:39,890
Basically, they show that
the convergence properties,

740
00:47:39,890 --> 00:47:41,770
they're basically comparable.

741
00:47:41,770 --> 00:47:44,350
But here you have fewer
parameters to learn.

742
00:47:44,350 --> 00:47:47,550
So it's basically quicker.

743
00:47:47,550 --> 00:47:48,050
Yeah.

744
00:48:12,690 --> 00:48:13,390
Good question.

745
00:48:13,390 --> 00:48:17,290
So the question is, what is the
intuition behind normalizing?

746
00:48:17,290 --> 00:48:22,010
So the intuition is that,
if you look at your model,

747
00:48:22,010 --> 00:48:24,170
you have several layers.

748
00:48:24,170 --> 00:48:27,570
In some layers your vector--

749
00:48:27,570 --> 00:48:29,390
your activation, to
be more precise--

750
00:48:29,390 --> 00:48:31,730
so do you know the
vector that you

751
00:48:31,730 --> 00:48:35,010
see that goes from here to here
is basically called activation.

752
00:48:35,010 --> 00:48:37,370
Sometimes the activation
has extreme values

753
00:48:37,370 --> 00:48:41,650
in one part of its component,
sometimes in another part.

754
00:48:41,650 --> 00:48:45,170
And the model is
typically having

755
00:48:45,170 --> 00:48:50,030
trouble in learning the
weights in each of these layers

756
00:48:50,030 --> 00:48:54,170
if these activations,
they vary too much.

757
00:48:54,170 --> 00:48:59,570
So the idea is to bring the
values of the components

758
00:48:59,570 --> 00:49:04,290
of the activation to
some range that is not

759
00:49:04,290 --> 00:49:09,952
too far off in some direction.

760
00:49:09,952 --> 00:49:11,410
So in case you're
interested, there

761
00:49:11,410 --> 00:49:16,130
is this key word,
internal covariate shift,

762
00:49:16,130 --> 00:49:18,610
which is basically the term
that is given to the phenomenon

763
00:49:18,610 --> 00:49:20,890
that I'm describing here.

764
00:49:20,890 --> 00:49:24,310
So yeah, that's the intuition.

765
00:49:24,310 --> 00:49:24,810
Yeah.

766
00:49:27,516 --> 00:49:28,805
Oh, great, great question.

767
00:49:28,805 --> 00:49:30,930
So question is, what is
the difference between this

768
00:49:30,930 --> 00:49:32,330
and batch normalization?

769
00:49:32,330 --> 00:49:36,675
So batch normalization
is normalization

770
00:49:36,675 --> 00:49:38,050
across the other
dimension, which

771
00:49:38,050 --> 00:49:41,410
is the dimension of the batch.

772
00:49:41,410 --> 00:49:44,690
So let's suppose you
have a bunch of vectors.

773
00:49:44,690 --> 00:49:49,780
What you do is you normalize
each component with respect

774
00:49:49,780 --> 00:49:55,120
to all the other components
for the same dimension,

775
00:49:55,120 --> 00:49:57,540
but of the other vectors.

776
00:49:57,540 --> 00:50:01,380
So you can think of it as just
another way of normalizing.

777
00:50:01,380 --> 00:50:03,460
But that being
said, when it comes

778
00:50:03,460 --> 00:50:05,960
to these
transformer-based models,

779
00:50:05,960 --> 00:50:08,860
typically people use
LayerNorm, probably

780
00:50:08,860 --> 00:50:10,660
because empirically
it works better.

781
00:50:10,660 --> 00:50:15,580
But also because
BatchNorm, you're

782
00:50:15,580 --> 00:50:19,220
basically also
dependent on the batch.

783
00:50:19,220 --> 00:50:23,420
And it can introduce, I guess,
differences between training

784
00:50:23,420 --> 00:50:24,520
and then inference.

785
00:50:24,520 --> 00:50:26,440
So that's basically
the reason why.

786
00:50:30,260 --> 00:50:32,560
Cool, great.

787
00:50:32,560 --> 00:50:34,600
So we've seen
position embeddings.

788
00:50:34,600 --> 00:50:36,760
We've seen layer normalization.

789
00:50:36,760 --> 00:50:39,860
So now we're going to see
a third important component

790
00:50:39,860 --> 00:50:44,460
of the transformer,
which is the attention.

791
00:50:44,460 --> 00:50:46,820
And in particular, I
guess there is something

792
00:50:46,820 --> 00:50:48,400
I've not really emphasized.

793
00:50:48,400 --> 00:50:51,580
But when you do
self-attention, you're

794
00:50:51,580 --> 00:50:57,020
basically letting every token
interact with all other tokens.

795
00:50:57,020 --> 00:50:59,380
So when you look at,
let's, say a matrix

796
00:50:59,380 --> 00:51:03,660
that shows all the
interactions, so you

797
00:51:03,660 --> 00:51:06,060
have n, the sequence length.

798
00:51:06,060 --> 00:51:08,220
And the sequence
length, you basically

799
00:51:08,220 --> 00:51:14,980
have o of n squared complexity,
which is a lot, especially

800
00:51:14,980 --> 00:51:17,000
as n grows longer.

801
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:23,300
So people have tried to
approximate this o of n squared

802
00:51:23,300 --> 00:51:25,700
into something that is a
little bit more tractable,

803
00:51:25,700 --> 00:51:30,220
but does not lose
the performance.

804
00:51:30,220 --> 00:51:34,340
So there is this paper in 2020
that came out, "LongFormer."

805
00:51:34,340 --> 00:51:37,700
So what it did was just
try different versions

806
00:51:37,700 --> 00:51:42,580
of the attention by restricting
the window at which it operates.

807
00:51:42,580 --> 00:51:46,940
So here, instead of letting each
token interact with everyone,

808
00:51:46,940 --> 00:51:52,120
each token only interacts
with its neighborhood.

809
00:51:52,120 --> 00:51:52,620
Yeah.

810
00:51:55,980 --> 00:51:58,040
Oh, again, a great question.

811
00:51:58,040 --> 00:52:02,660
So question is, do you do that
after the attention matrix

812
00:52:02,660 --> 00:52:03,940
computation?

813
00:52:03,940 --> 00:52:06,140
You mean the softmax,
right, softmax?

814
00:52:06,140 --> 00:52:07,740
So you raise a
great point, which

815
00:52:07,740 --> 00:52:10,860
is, if you do the
softmax of everything,

816
00:52:10,860 --> 00:52:12,860
why would you do this?

817
00:52:12,860 --> 00:52:17,340
So in practice there is a
bunch of implementations

818
00:52:17,340 --> 00:52:19,780
that does a clever--

819
00:52:19,780 --> 00:52:21,100
so it's called tiling--

820
00:52:21,100 --> 00:52:24,620
a bunch of clever
operations that

821
00:52:24,620 --> 00:52:27,980
do not involve this
huge matrix operation

822
00:52:27,980 --> 00:52:30,785
that you see in the softmax.

823
00:52:30,785 --> 00:52:35,140
Again, I guess, like against the
softmax of qk transpose over d.

824
00:52:35,140 --> 00:52:37,340
You're not going to
compute the whole thing.

825
00:52:37,340 --> 00:52:40,380
You're going to have
some cleverness in how

826
00:52:40,380 --> 00:52:42,080
you compute that, basically.

827
00:52:54,380 --> 00:52:59,060
Yeah, so the question is,
can it be something that's

828
00:52:59,060 --> 00:53:00,600
comparable to convolutions?

829
00:53:00,600 --> 00:53:03,340
And we're going to
see that in a second.

830
00:53:03,340 --> 00:53:06,663
But you have some similarities
with the vision world.

831
00:53:06,663 --> 00:53:08,330
And we're going to
see that in a second.

832
00:53:11,100 --> 00:53:12,520
Cool.

833
00:53:12,520 --> 00:53:19,860
So nowadays when you have local
attention like this, like this,

834
00:53:19,860 --> 00:53:24,540
people use the term
sliding window attention.

835
00:53:24,540 --> 00:53:26,180
So when they use
that term, they mean

836
00:53:26,180 --> 00:53:29,180
this, which is basically just
restricting the attention

837
00:53:29,180 --> 00:53:32,860
to neighboring tokens.

838
00:53:32,860 --> 00:53:37,820
And nowadays what people
do is in some layers

839
00:53:37,820 --> 00:53:40,780
they will have local attention.

840
00:53:40,780 --> 00:53:44,580
In some others, they will
have global attention.

841
00:53:44,580 --> 00:53:47,900
And they interleave
these layers.

842
00:53:47,900 --> 00:53:50,060
So depending on the
model, they typically

843
00:53:50,060 --> 00:53:51,360
try different combinations.

844
00:53:51,360 --> 00:53:54,140
So there's not a set recipe.

845
00:53:54,140 --> 00:53:58,060
But it's typically something
that is used nowadays.

846
00:53:58,060 --> 00:54:02,860
So the window here, I mean,
for, illustrative, purposes,

847
00:54:02,860 --> 00:54:05,400
the window is super
small in my illustration.

848
00:54:05,400 --> 00:54:10,100
But I guess nowadays
with the sequence lengths

849
00:54:10,100 --> 00:54:12,700
that can be very big, you can
think of this window as being,

850
00:54:12,700 --> 00:54:14,400
o of several, thousands.

851
00:54:20,820 --> 00:54:22,880
And just to give
you another example.

852
00:54:22,880 --> 00:54:29,080
So back to the convolution
comparison that you mentioned.

853
00:54:29,080 --> 00:54:33,440
So you have some architectures.

854
00:54:33,440 --> 00:54:36,660
And here I'm going to take
the example of a mistral that

855
00:54:36,660 --> 00:54:40,880
has these sliding window
attention at every layer.

856
00:54:40,880 --> 00:54:44,700
But then when you
think about it,

857
00:54:44,700 --> 00:54:48,540
the token here can attend
up to the token here,

858
00:54:48,540 --> 00:54:50,100
but then the token
here can attend up

859
00:54:50,100 --> 00:54:53,700
to the token here,
et cetera, et cetera.

860
00:54:53,700 --> 00:54:56,220
So I guess, if you
think about it,

861
00:54:56,220 --> 00:54:59,380
it's similar to the
idea of the receptive

862
00:54:59,380 --> 00:55:01,020
field in computer vision.

863
00:55:01,020 --> 00:55:04,660
So I'm not sure if you're
familiar or from the computer

864
00:55:04,660 --> 00:55:05,320
vision world.

865
00:55:05,320 --> 00:55:13,660
But if you are, what this
means is just taking one token

866
00:55:13,660 --> 00:55:18,220
and trying to think
what other tokens has

867
00:55:18,220 --> 00:55:21,140
this token effectively
interacted with,

868
00:55:21,140 --> 00:55:25,725
which is basically the question
that people also sometimes ask.

869
00:55:25,725 --> 00:55:27,100
When they do
convolution, they're

870
00:55:27,100 --> 00:55:31,640
like, OK, so this value,
what are the values

871
00:55:31,640 --> 00:55:33,980
did it actually see?

872
00:55:33,980 --> 00:55:38,940
So you can also
think it this way.

873
00:55:38,940 --> 00:55:43,100
OK, so first
variation is, instead

874
00:55:43,100 --> 00:55:48,180
of doing the full
n by n attention,

875
00:55:48,180 --> 00:55:51,980
people sometimes
do local attention.

876
00:55:51,980 --> 00:55:56,300
The second variation that
is orthogonal to all of this

877
00:55:56,300 --> 00:56:04,540
is to not have one
projection matrix per head,

878
00:56:04,540 --> 00:56:10,100
but to share projection
matrices across heads.

879
00:56:10,100 --> 00:56:15,140
So here the idea is you
have, let's say, h heads.

880
00:56:15,140 --> 00:56:19,900
The idea is you're going to
have some number of projection

881
00:56:19,900 --> 00:56:22,060
matrices for the query.

882
00:56:22,060 --> 00:56:23,820
But then what you're
going to do is

883
00:56:23,820 --> 00:56:29,740
to group the projection matrices
for the key and the value

884
00:56:29,740 --> 00:56:32,350
that you're going to share
across several heads.

885
00:56:34,980 --> 00:56:38,180
Now you may ask, why do you
share projection matrices

886
00:56:38,180 --> 00:56:42,195
for the keys and the values,
but not for the queries?

887
00:56:42,195 --> 00:56:46,980
Is this the question
that you're wondering?

888
00:56:46,980 --> 00:56:53,820
Well here, I guess, people
do things to just try out

889
00:56:53,820 --> 00:56:55,160
if something works or not.

890
00:56:55,160 --> 00:56:57,820
I guess here you can
intuitively think

891
00:56:57,820 --> 00:57:01,180
that the query is basically
wondering if something

892
00:57:01,180 --> 00:57:02,640
is similar to another thing.

893
00:57:02,640 --> 00:57:06,640
So I guess you can ask yourself
this question in different ways.

894
00:57:06,640 --> 00:57:11,660
So it may make sense
to keep that diversity.

895
00:57:11,660 --> 00:57:16,140
But one of the core reasons why
we choose to group projection

896
00:57:16,140 --> 00:57:18,100
matrices for the
keys and the values

897
00:57:18,100 --> 00:57:25,540
and not the query is
because, when you decode,

898
00:57:25,540 --> 00:57:31,740
you perform attention between
the current word and all

899
00:57:31,740 --> 00:57:34,580
the words before.

900
00:57:34,580 --> 00:57:38,680
So in other words, every
time you generate a new word,

901
00:57:38,680 --> 00:57:43,900
you're going to attend that
word to all the words before.

902
00:57:43,900 --> 00:57:47,548
So the keys and the values,
they're going to come up a lot.

903
00:57:47,548 --> 00:57:49,340
So every time you want
to decode something,

904
00:57:49,340 --> 00:57:53,980
you need to attend to all
other things, again and again.

905
00:57:53,980 --> 00:57:56,620
So we're going to
see in, I think,

906
00:57:56,620 --> 00:57:59,260
next, lecture there's
something called

907
00:57:59,260 --> 00:58:07,180
the KV cache, which basically
saves the values of the keys

908
00:58:07,180 --> 00:58:09,300
and values.

909
00:58:09,300 --> 00:58:12,500
And one thing that we
want is for that cache

910
00:58:12,500 --> 00:58:16,220
to not become too big.

911
00:58:16,220 --> 00:58:20,460
So if you share projection
matrices across heads,

912
00:58:20,460 --> 00:58:23,520
just allows you to save
a little bit of space,

913
00:58:23,520 --> 00:58:25,900
a little bit of memory.

914
00:58:25,900 --> 00:58:28,860
That's the why.

915
00:58:28,860 --> 00:58:30,520
Does that roughly make sense?

916
00:58:33,190 --> 00:58:34,430
OK, cool.

917
00:58:34,430 --> 00:58:39,510
So speaking of that, there are
some variations as to, I guess,

918
00:58:39,510 --> 00:58:44,070
just how many projection
matrices to share.

919
00:58:44,070 --> 00:58:47,270
So you have the
extreme example where

920
00:58:47,270 --> 00:58:51,950
all h heads, they all
share the same projection

921
00:58:51,950 --> 00:58:56,670
matrices for v and k.

922
00:58:56,670 --> 00:58:58,910
And in that case,
this method is called

923
00:58:58,910 --> 00:59:04,110
MQA, Multi-Query Attention.

924
00:59:04,110 --> 00:59:11,470
You have the in-between
case where you share g,

925
00:59:11,470 --> 00:59:16,270
where g is the number of groups
g projection matrices for v

926
00:59:16,270 --> 00:59:17,430
and k.

927
00:59:17,430 --> 00:59:24,310
And then you have groups of
size, let's say, h over g.

928
00:59:24,310 --> 00:59:30,150
So this one is called
Group Query Attention, GQA.

929
00:59:30,150 --> 00:59:33,670
And then you have the case
that you are very familiar

930
00:59:33,670 --> 00:59:36,390
with from the
transformer, which is

931
00:59:36,390 --> 00:59:43,330
every head has its own query
projection, key projection,

932
00:59:43,330 --> 00:59:45,190
and value projection matrices.

933
00:59:45,190 --> 00:59:48,290
And this is the standard,
multi-head attention.

934
00:59:53,590 --> 00:59:54,570
Cool.

935
00:59:54,570 --> 00:59:59,150
So I'm, going to just take a
pause to see if what I mentioned

936
00:59:59,150 --> 01:00:00,150
makes sense.

