1001
01:03:26,310 --> 01:03:29,870
But also later on, you
see more architectures

1002
01:03:29,870 --> 01:03:32,430
that built on top of it.

1003
01:03:32,430 --> 01:03:38,010
So here we talk about
the T5 family of models.

1004
01:03:38,010 --> 01:03:44,410
So T5 is a paper that's an
abbreviation of multiple Ts.

1005
01:03:44,410 --> 01:03:48,110
So the first one is transfer,
and then it's text-to-text,

1006
01:03:48,110 --> 01:03:49,630
transformers.

1007
01:03:49,630 --> 01:03:54,110
So this is where the
T5 naming comes from.

1008
01:03:54,110 --> 01:03:56,990
And then it's derived
into multiple versions.

1009
01:03:56,990 --> 01:04:00,150
So the T5 is like
the vanilla paper.

1010
01:04:00,150 --> 01:04:02,670
And then it had mT5.

1011
01:04:02,670 --> 01:04:06,470
m stands for
multilingual where there

1012
01:04:06,470 --> 01:04:09,150
was some more work on the
data it was trained on,

1013
01:04:09,150 --> 01:04:14,750
as well as the vocabulary
that it was computed over.

1014
01:04:14,750 --> 01:04:18,550
And then you have
ByT5, which is some

1015
01:04:18,550 --> 01:04:24,430
of tokenizer-free method of
all of this where you forego

1016
01:04:24,430 --> 01:04:26,990
of the fact of tokenizing.

1017
01:04:26,990 --> 01:04:29,750
And instead of
that, you basically

1018
01:04:29,750 --> 01:04:31,630
operate at the byte level.

1019
01:04:31,630 --> 01:04:33,950
So By is like byte.

1020
01:04:33,950 --> 01:04:37,270
And basically, you
have a vocabulary size

1021
01:04:37,270 --> 01:04:38,710
that is much smaller.

1022
01:04:38,710 --> 01:04:42,030
So instead of
having an o of 30k,

1023
01:04:42,030 --> 01:04:45,070
you have 2 to the power of 8.

1024
01:04:45,070 --> 01:04:47,390
So a byte is 8 bits.

1025
01:04:47,390 --> 01:04:52,010
And then you can represent
every character into bytes.

1026
01:04:52,010 --> 01:04:53,010
So that's what they do.

1027
01:04:55,990 --> 01:04:56,970
OK, great.

1028
01:04:56,970 --> 01:04:58,550
And then one thing
I want to mention

1029
01:04:58,550 --> 01:05:03,390
regarding the T5 family is that
the objective function changes

1030
01:05:03,390 --> 01:05:07,950
a bit with what the
original transformer did.

1031
01:05:07,950 --> 01:05:11,630
So the original transformer
did next token prediction

1032
01:05:11,630 --> 01:05:13,470
for the training task.

1033
01:05:13,470 --> 01:05:15,630
But the T5 family,
what they did is

1034
01:05:15,630 --> 01:05:23,630
that they operated on the
so-called span corruption task.

1035
01:05:23,630 --> 01:05:26,350
So basically you would
have your sentence

1036
01:05:26,350 --> 01:05:29,790
as an input to the encoder.

1037
01:05:29,790 --> 01:05:33,030
And instead of putting
everything to the encoder,

1038
01:05:33,030 --> 01:05:35,150
you would leave blanks.

1039
01:05:35,150 --> 01:05:39,030
And this is what we
call span corruption.

1040
01:05:39,030 --> 01:05:41,470
And then the span
corruption could be

1041
01:05:41,470 --> 01:05:44,790
one or multiple tokens missing.

1042
01:05:44,790 --> 01:05:49,810
So if I want to give an
example, so for example,

1043
01:05:49,810 --> 01:05:52,690
my teddy bear is
cute and reading.

1044
01:05:52,690 --> 01:05:58,290
So you could have my teddy bear
span corrupted, and is reading.

1045
01:05:58,290 --> 01:06:03,390
So that could be one
potential encoder input.

1046
01:06:03,390 --> 01:06:06,630
And then you could
have up to n--

1047
01:06:06,630 --> 01:06:08,750
I mean, n is the
parameterization

1048
01:06:08,750 --> 01:06:10,930
of the number of spans
that are corrupted.

1049
01:06:10,930 --> 01:06:14,110
So you would have
n such tokens here.

1050
01:06:14,110 --> 01:06:18,490
And then the T5 families
calls them sentinel tokens.

1051
01:06:18,490 --> 01:06:20,190
So if you see
sentinel tokens, they

1052
01:06:20,190 --> 01:06:24,190
represent a span of
corrupted tokens.

1053
01:06:24,190 --> 01:06:26,510
So you have them
here in the encoder.

1054
01:06:26,510 --> 01:06:30,430
And then the decoder's
work is to find

1055
01:06:30,430 --> 01:06:33,690
each of these spans in series.

1056
01:06:33,690 --> 01:06:36,790
So you start with a
token that denotes

1057
01:06:36,790 --> 01:06:38,790
the first corrupted span.

1058
01:06:38,790 --> 01:06:41,150
And then you start
the decoding process

1059
01:06:41,150 --> 01:06:47,710
until it hits a prediction that
predicts the next sentinel token

1060
01:06:47,710 --> 01:06:54,470
up to the n plus 1, 1, where
the tokens that are decoded

1061
01:06:54,470 --> 01:06:57,390
between two consecutive
sentinel tokens

1062
01:06:57,390 --> 01:07:03,070
corresponds to the corrupted
spans that are recovered.

1063
01:07:03,070 --> 01:07:05,110
So these parentheses
is basically

1064
01:07:05,110 --> 01:07:08,730
a shift from the next token
prediction objective function.

1065
01:07:08,730 --> 01:07:09,230
Yep.

1066
01:07:27,040 --> 01:07:27,540
Yeah.

1067
01:07:27,540 --> 01:07:30,280
So the question is, can you
elaborate with the decoding

1068
01:07:30,280 --> 01:07:30,860
process?

1069
01:07:30,860 --> 01:07:34,020
So what you said regarding the
reconstruction is exactly right.

1070
01:07:34,020 --> 01:07:38,760
So you have sentinel tokens
that denote some missing text.

1071
01:07:38,760 --> 01:07:41,340
So what you want to decode
is that missing text.

1072
01:07:41,340 --> 01:07:44,520
So the decoder output
will be exactly

1073
01:07:44,520 --> 01:07:48,040
like each span reconstructed.

1074
01:07:48,040 --> 01:07:50,160
And then if you want to
know how training works,

1075
01:07:50,160 --> 01:07:54,080
you do a teacher-forcing
mechanism

1076
01:07:54,080 --> 01:07:57,540
where you input
everything in the decoder,

1077
01:07:57,540 --> 01:08:00,460
and then try to reconstruct
everything at once.

1078
01:08:00,460 --> 01:08:04,500
So any other questions?

1079
01:08:07,180 --> 01:08:07,680
Great.

1080
01:08:10,360 --> 01:08:13,200
And then now we're going
to talk about another class

1081
01:08:13,200 --> 01:08:18,640
of transformers where basically
you have this encoder/decoder

1082
01:08:18,640 --> 01:08:22,960
structure, where you just forget
about the decoder and then just

1083
01:08:22,960 --> 01:08:25,080
deal with the encoder.

1084
01:08:25,080 --> 01:08:30,080
So you might tell me, OK, hey,
you cannot do generation with

1085
01:08:30,080 --> 01:08:30,580
this.

1086
01:08:30,580 --> 01:08:33,469
And then I would respond to you,
yes, that's exactly the point.

1087
01:08:37,000 --> 01:08:38,800
So it has encoder
representations

1088
01:08:38,800 --> 01:08:42,479
that can be used for
tasks that might be more

1089
01:08:42,479 --> 01:08:44,279
geared towards classification.

1090
01:08:44,279 --> 01:08:49,160
So sentiment extraction,
token classification,

1091
01:08:49,160 --> 01:08:53,240
all of these things that used to
be done with specific language

1092
01:08:53,240 --> 01:08:56,279
models, they can be
done with the encoder

1093
01:08:56,279 --> 01:08:58,680
part of the transformer.

1094
01:08:58,680 --> 01:09:02,359
And we're going to
dive deeper a bit later

1095
01:09:02,359 --> 01:09:06,500
into a three-key
encoder only models.

1096
01:09:06,500 --> 01:09:10,439
So BERT, which is
like the central one,

1097
01:09:10,439 --> 01:09:12,399
I would say in this
landscape, and then

1098
01:09:12,399 --> 01:09:16,279
two other architectures,
DistilBERT and RoBERTa,

1099
01:09:16,279 --> 01:09:20,760
that are investigating
on axis of improvements.

1100
01:09:20,760 --> 01:09:24,160
So it's going to be good to see.

1101
01:09:24,160 --> 01:09:27,399
So OK, great.

1102
01:09:27,399 --> 01:09:29,979
And then there is
one last class.

1103
01:09:29,979 --> 01:09:33,479
So as Afshine just
mentioned, two days

1104
01:09:33,479 --> 01:09:38,399
LLMs, they remove the
encoder part altogether.

1105
01:09:38,399 --> 01:09:40,680
And then when you
have no encoder,

1106
01:09:40,680 --> 01:09:42,880
you don't have your
encoder embeddings

1107
01:09:42,880 --> 01:09:45,200
at the end of your
stacked encoders

1108
01:09:45,200 --> 01:09:49,140
that could be fed to
the cross-attention.

1109
01:09:49,140 --> 01:09:52,640
So this module
disappears altogether.

1110
01:09:52,640 --> 01:09:55,320
So each decoder
that is stacked just

1111
01:09:55,320 --> 01:10:02,640
has masked self-attention
and an FFN as part of it.

1112
01:10:02,640 --> 01:10:06,120
And yeah, that's
basically something

1113
01:10:06,120 --> 01:10:08,900
that has caught up since then.

1114
01:10:08,900 --> 01:10:11,120
Because when you look at
the popularity of each

1115
01:10:11,120 --> 01:10:14,440
of these models,
so you used to have

1116
01:10:14,440 --> 01:10:17,560
these transformer-like
architecture that was popular

1117
01:10:17,560 --> 01:10:20,920
towards the beginning, where
the main hypothesis was

1118
01:10:20,920 --> 01:10:24,920
that the encoder part is
very useful for getting

1119
01:10:24,920 --> 01:10:28,760
to the decoder's representation.

1120
01:10:28,760 --> 01:10:32,000
But as time went,
people realized

1121
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:36,000
that your compute budget
could be best invested

1122
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:38,240
in the decoder only.

1123
01:10:38,240 --> 01:10:44,160
And then there has been more
investment into the kind

1124
01:10:44,160 --> 01:10:48,200
of tasks that is, I would
say, easiest to scale up

1125
01:10:48,200 --> 01:10:50,800
and generalize--
next-word prediction--

1126
01:10:50,800 --> 01:10:54,240
as opposed to the task
I just mentioned for T5,

1127
01:10:54,240 --> 01:10:57,740
which might be more bespoke.

1128
01:10:57,740 --> 01:10:59,880
So you need to corrupt things.

1129
01:10:59,880 --> 01:11:01,660
So it's more complex.

1130
01:11:01,660 --> 01:11:04,320
Whereas next-word
prediction is, I would say,

1131
01:11:04,320 --> 01:11:05,820
the simplest thing you can do.

1132
01:11:05,820 --> 01:11:09,720
And it proved to be
wonders and well-aligned

1133
01:11:09,720 --> 01:11:14,760
with the task of being a
helpful kind of chatbot,

1134
01:11:14,760 --> 01:11:19,520
which is like two days'
applications mainly.

1135
01:11:19,520 --> 01:11:24,080
And then the decoder-only
architectures-- so I'm not

1136
01:11:24,080 --> 01:11:26,680
going to talk about them today.

1137
01:11:26,680 --> 01:11:30,600
But it's going to be the central
part of the next lectures

1138
01:11:30,600 --> 01:11:35,480
when we're going to talk
about LLMs more and more.

1139
01:11:35,480 --> 01:11:36,840
OK, awesome.

1140
01:11:36,840 --> 01:11:41,340
So now we can dive
deep, as promised,

1141
01:11:41,340 --> 01:11:45,960
into encoder-only
architectures and with BERT.

1142
01:11:45,960 --> 01:11:52,040
So first we're going to start
by seeing what does BERT mean.

1143
01:11:52,040 --> 01:11:58,320
So BERT, it's an acronym that
denotes Bidirectional Encoder

1144
01:11:58,320 --> 01:12:01,080
Representations
from Transformers.

1145
01:12:01,080 --> 01:12:03,480
And we're going to
see together how

1146
01:12:03,480 --> 01:12:06,800
does each section of this
acronym, what does it

1147
01:12:06,800 --> 01:12:08,480
correspond to?

1148
01:12:08,480 --> 01:12:11,780
So let's just start
with the encoder part,

1149
01:12:11,780 --> 01:12:15,560
which is the easiest to grasp.

1150
01:12:15,560 --> 01:12:18,520
So as we said, we just
dropped the decoder.

1151
01:12:18,520 --> 01:12:21,280
So this encoder from
transformer is basically

1152
01:12:21,280 --> 01:12:24,200
exactly what it means.

1153
01:12:24,200 --> 01:12:32,080
Now on the other part, so why do
we talk about bidirectionality?

1154
01:12:32,080 --> 01:12:39,240
So it's a way, so the
paper's result is remarkable,

1155
01:12:39,240 --> 01:12:43,040
because we are able
from a given input

1156
01:12:43,040 --> 01:12:49,120
to get output representations
that have attended to everything

1157
01:12:49,120 --> 01:12:51,080
for each token.

1158
01:12:51,080 --> 01:12:53,080
And this is the case.

1159
01:12:53,080 --> 01:12:55,920
Because since we only
have the encoder,

1160
01:12:55,920 --> 01:12:58,960
we have this
self-attention layer

1161
01:12:58,960 --> 01:13:02,440
that truly attends
to every other token.

1162
01:13:02,440 --> 01:13:07,760
And this is in contrast with
the masked self-attention

1163
01:13:07,760 --> 01:13:12,120
that you have where we said that
the mask is making the attention

1164
01:13:12,120 --> 01:13:14,360
mechanism causal.

1165
01:13:14,360 --> 01:13:18,680
So every token can attend
to itself and to the tokens

1166
01:13:18,680 --> 01:13:19,983
before it.

1167
01:13:19,983 --> 01:13:21,400
And this is, by
the way, something

1168
01:13:21,400 --> 01:13:25,520
that the authors discuss
a lot in the paper,

1169
01:13:25,520 --> 01:13:30,306
saying that GPT came out, GPT
they're not truly bidirectional.

1170
01:13:30,306 --> 01:13:33,880
And then these encodings that
can be used for classification

1171
01:13:33,880 --> 01:13:37,720
tasks, they truly are.

1172
01:13:37,720 --> 01:13:40,660
Any questions?

1173
01:13:40,660 --> 01:13:41,160
Yep.

1174
01:13:50,280 --> 01:13:51,180
Yep, that's right.

1175
01:13:51,180 --> 01:13:54,140
So the question is, when
you don't have the mask,

1176
01:13:54,140 --> 01:13:55,680
each token can
attend to each other.

1177
01:13:55,680 --> 01:13:56,780
That's exactly right.

1178
01:13:56,780 --> 01:13:58,960
And then the mask
is exactly there

1179
01:13:58,960 --> 01:14:04,960
to prevent links from tokens
to those that come after them.

1180
01:14:04,960 --> 01:14:07,120
Yeah.

1181
01:14:07,120 --> 01:14:09,160
OK, great.

1182
01:14:09,160 --> 01:14:12,580
So I just want to put
this paper in context.

1183
01:14:12,580 --> 01:14:16,480
And the field of NLP
was booming back then.

1184
01:14:16,480 --> 01:14:18,480
So you had another
landmark paper

1185
01:14:18,480 --> 01:14:21,740
that same year, which
was called ELMo,

1186
01:14:21,740 --> 01:14:24,800
so Embeddings from
Language Models.

1187
01:14:24,800 --> 01:14:27,720
And I would say that
the timing of that paper

1188
01:14:27,720 --> 01:14:31,120
was a bit unfortunate,
because it truly

1189
01:14:31,120 --> 01:14:35,640
had new insights
of also building

1190
01:14:35,640 --> 01:14:37,380
bidirectional representations.

1191
01:14:37,380 --> 01:14:39,760
But it just turns out
that it came the same year

1192
01:14:39,760 --> 01:14:44,800
as the transformer, as the kind
of transformer-based same line

1193
01:14:44,800 --> 01:14:45,500
of work.

1194
01:14:45,500 --> 01:14:49,600
So it got a bit masked by it.

1195
01:14:49,600 --> 01:14:52,460
So ELMo, just to
give the main lines,

1196
01:14:52,460 --> 01:14:56,200
it was based on a
bidirectional LSTM

1197
01:14:56,200 --> 01:14:59,600
where you had
multiple layers, each

1198
01:14:59,600 --> 01:15:01,100
stacked on top of each other.

1199
01:15:01,100 --> 01:15:04,800
And basically you
were able to build

1200
01:15:04,800 --> 01:15:08,400
a bidirectional
representation for each word,

1201
01:15:08,400 --> 01:15:10,840
thanks to this architecture.

1202
01:15:10,840 --> 01:15:17,700
And so why didn't it
become as popular as BERT?

1203
01:15:17,700 --> 01:15:20,160
It's because you had
the same downsides

1204
01:15:20,160 --> 01:15:22,520
as the previous models,
where basically it's

1205
01:15:22,520 --> 01:15:27,960
hard to scale because
of this recurrence.

1206
01:15:27,960 --> 01:15:33,160
And I think a lot of you, when
you think about ELMo and BERT,

1207
01:15:33,160 --> 01:15:36,840
you don't think about
these papers at first,

1208
01:15:36,840 --> 01:15:40,680
because they are characters
in Sesame Street.

1209
01:15:40,680 --> 01:15:44,120
And I grew up in a
place where I did not

1210
01:15:44,120 --> 01:15:45,580
know about Sesame Street.

1211
01:15:45,580 --> 01:15:47,980
So for me, ELMo and BERT
is like paper names.

1212
01:15:47,980 --> 01:15:52,243
But it might be what
represents to you at first.

1213
01:15:52,243 --> 01:15:53,660
So I thought that
was quite funny.

1214
01:15:53,660 --> 01:15:58,540
And then researchers, they
are generally quite playful.

1215
01:15:58,540 --> 01:16:03,700
They try to fit their
acronyms into themes.

1216
01:16:03,700 --> 01:16:08,430
So if you look at paper names,
you will get entertained.

1217
01:16:11,450 --> 01:16:13,090
OK, great.

1218
01:16:13,090 --> 01:16:16,330
So to dive deeper
into what I mentioned

1219
01:16:16,330 --> 01:16:19,210
to be the goal of
encoder-only models,

1220
01:16:19,210 --> 01:16:23,570
so you have your set
of tokens as input.

1221
01:16:23,570 --> 01:16:27,050
And the goal here
is to perform tasks

1222
01:16:27,050 --> 01:16:30,810
that might be
focused on projecting

1223
01:16:30,810 --> 01:16:33,490
some representation somewhere,
so typically classification

1224
01:16:33,490 --> 01:16:34,810
tasks.

1225
01:16:34,810 --> 01:16:41,090
And here, the way BERT
works is very specific.

1226
01:16:41,090 --> 01:16:43,210
So you have two kinds
of tokens that you

1227
01:16:43,210 --> 01:16:46,370
will see are structural here.

1228
01:16:46,370 --> 01:16:53,170
So you have first the CLS token,
which stands for classification.

1229
01:16:53,170 --> 01:16:55,690
And it's basically
a placeholder token

1230
01:16:55,690 --> 01:17:00,730
that is put at the beginning
of the sequence that will then,

1231
01:17:00,730 --> 01:17:03,330
at the end of the
whole attention

1232
01:17:03,330 --> 01:17:07,570
and then projection and the
whole encoder mechanism,

1233
01:17:07,570 --> 01:17:10,930
be projected into an
embedding that we can then

1234
01:17:10,930 --> 01:17:13,210
use for classification.

1235
01:17:13,210 --> 01:17:15,970
So CLS is just some
kind of placeholder

1236
01:17:15,970 --> 01:17:20,130
that will carry the
bidirectional information

1237
01:17:20,130 --> 01:17:23,010
of your whole input.

1238
01:17:23,010 --> 01:17:27,750
And another token that might be
useful to see is this SEP token.

1239
01:17:27,750 --> 01:17:30,050
So it's like separator.

1240
01:17:30,050 --> 01:17:32,730
And then you will
see very soon we're

1241
01:17:32,730 --> 01:17:36,670
going to see the objective
functions that it operates on.

1242
01:17:36,670 --> 01:17:41,530
It aims at separating
two sentences.

1243
01:17:41,530 --> 01:17:43,530
Yeah.

1244
01:17:43,530 --> 01:17:45,570
So this is the very high level.

1245
01:17:45,570 --> 01:17:49,970
And then so one thing
that is very interesting

1246
01:17:49,970 --> 01:17:53,890
to see with this model is
that you have this concept

1247
01:17:53,890 --> 01:17:56,090
of multi-stage training.

1248
01:17:56,090 --> 01:17:59,810
So you don't train
the model in one shot.

1249
01:17:59,810 --> 01:18:02,250
You do it in multiple stages.

1250
01:18:02,250 --> 01:18:06,170
So the first stage is
aimed at being aligned

1251
01:18:06,170 --> 01:18:07,930
with the task of interest.

1252
01:18:07,930 --> 01:18:11,570
And so this is what
we call pre-training.

1253
01:18:11,570 --> 01:18:14,770
And this pre-training,
we will see in detail,

1254
01:18:14,770 --> 01:18:19,290
is done with two objective
functions that are respectively

1255
01:18:19,290 --> 01:18:20,710
MLM and NSP.

1256
01:18:20,710 --> 01:18:25,650
So MLM stands for
Masked Language Model.

1257
01:18:25,650 --> 01:18:30,330
And NSP is the Next
Sentence Prediction.

1258
01:18:30,330 --> 01:18:32,970
So masked language
model, it's a way

1259
01:18:32,970 --> 01:18:35,930
for the model to learn
the internal structure

1260
01:18:35,930 --> 01:18:39,090
of the inputs.

1261
01:18:39,090 --> 01:18:42,650
And then NSP, it
might be seen as a way

1262
01:18:42,650 --> 01:18:46,390
to see if the ordering
of sentences makes sense.

1263
01:18:46,390 --> 01:18:49,070
So we're going to go a
bit deeper into each,

1264
01:18:49,070 --> 01:18:52,530
but it's a combination
of objective function

1265
01:18:52,530 --> 01:18:58,130
that the authors assumed
to be helpful for learning

1266
01:18:58,130 --> 01:19:03,090
general embeddings
of high quality.

1267
01:19:03,090 --> 01:19:03,590
OK.

1268
01:19:03,590 --> 01:19:05,450
So the second thing
that I want to mention

1269
01:19:05,450 --> 01:19:07,470
is that, once you
have all of this,

1270
01:19:07,470 --> 01:19:11,970
you have a further stage where
you keep the embeddings that you

1271
01:19:11,970 --> 01:19:13,210
have learned.

1272
01:19:13,210 --> 01:19:17,250
And then you attach to it some
other network, like typically

1273
01:19:17,250 --> 01:19:22,530
a linear projection,
to then fine tune

1274
01:19:22,530 --> 01:19:26,690
the embeddings that you have
learned into some target task.

1275
01:19:26,690 --> 01:19:29,270
So this is what we
call fine tuning.

1276
01:19:29,270 --> 01:19:29,770
Yep.

1277
01:19:46,770 --> 01:19:47,550
So yeah.

1278
01:19:47,550 --> 01:19:52,510
So the question is, do we still
have just an encoder here?

1279
01:19:52,510 --> 01:19:55,010
Because a next-sentence
prediction

1280
01:19:55,010 --> 01:19:57,510
could be seen as a decoder task.

1281
01:19:57,510 --> 01:19:59,770
So actually I'm going
to go in detail.

1282
01:19:59,770 --> 01:20:01,370
The next-sentence
prediction task

1283
01:20:01,370 --> 01:20:05,590
is actually us putting two
sentences, one after the other,

1284
01:20:05,590 --> 01:20:10,090
and predicting whether
they are truly consecutive.

1285
01:20:10,090 --> 01:20:12,650
So it's a classification task.

1286
01:20:12,650 --> 01:20:13,670
Yeah, great point.

1287
01:20:13,670 --> 01:20:17,330
And yeah, we're going to see
that in detail very soon.

1288
01:20:17,330 --> 01:20:21,690
So before we see
that in detail, I'm

1289
01:20:21,690 --> 01:20:26,210
going to discuss the pros and
cons that this method usually

1290
01:20:26,210 --> 01:20:27,010
has.

1291
01:20:27,010 --> 01:20:35,250
So regarding on the pro side,
this pre-training mechanism

1292
01:20:35,250 --> 01:20:38,590
can be done on fairly
unlabeled data.

1293
01:20:38,590 --> 01:20:41,385
So you still have this
next-sentence prediction task.

1294
01:20:41,385 --> 01:20:43,010
But this is something
that you control,

1295
01:20:43,010 --> 01:20:46,550
because you know which
sentences follow each other.

1296
01:20:46,550 --> 01:20:51,770
So it's something that you
know it's self-supervised.

1297
01:20:51,770 --> 01:20:54,370
And the masked language
model task, we're

1298
01:20:54,370 --> 01:20:57,770
going to see how it consists.

1299
01:20:57,770 --> 01:21:01,830
But it's also something
that is unsupervised.

1300
01:21:01,830 --> 01:21:04,610
So this is a very
interesting way

1301
01:21:04,610 --> 01:21:08,890
to learn interesting embeddings
out of unlabeled data.

1302
01:21:08,890 --> 01:21:12,050
And then in practice
is that we see

1303
01:21:12,050 --> 01:21:16,330
that these unlabeled data leads
to helpful representations being

1304
01:21:16,330 --> 01:21:17,370
learned.

1305
01:21:17,370 --> 01:21:20,930
And then you need very little
data to build on top of it.

1306
01:21:20,930 --> 01:21:24,530
So at the fine tuning
stage, you just

1307
01:21:24,530 --> 01:21:26,690
start from these
very nice embeddings

1308
01:21:26,690 --> 01:21:30,570
that you have learned, and you
just have a few weights to tune.

1309
01:21:30,570 --> 01:21:34,450
And then this usually leads
to a performance that exceeds

1310
01:21:34,450 --> 01:21:37,330
state of the art back then.

1311
01:21:37,330 --> 01:21:40,770
And then regarding
the downsides,

1312
01:21:40,770 --> 01:21:45,290
we have of course all
the text generation

1313
01:21:45,290 --> 01:21:48,690
tasks that are out of reach
because we don't have a decoder.

1314
01:21:48,690 --> 01:21:52,170
And also, we can see these
two stage process and the fact

1315
01:21:52,170 --> 01:21:55,490
that we need to
further tune embeddings

1316
01:21:55,490 --> 01:21:59,570
as something that
can be over hurdled.

1317
01:21:59,570 --> 01:22:04,170
So it might be, when you
compare this kind of methodology

1318
01:22:04,170 --> 01:22:08,130
with respect to more traditional
methods, that can be one shot.

1319
01:22:08,130 --> 01:22:11,810
This could be seen
as a downside.

1320
01:22:11,810 --> 01:22:13,010
OK, great.

1321
01:22:13,010 --> 01:22:18,630
And I have some names
regarding variants here.

1322
01:22:18,630 --> 01:22:21,870
We're going to dive deep into
two of them a bit later on.

1323
01:22:24,450 --> 01:22:24,950
OK.

1324
01:22:24,950 --> 01:22:27,910
So I want us to focus on
the original transformer.

1325
01:22:27,910 --> 01:22:31,770
And we're going to go step by
step into what happened to it,

1326
01:22:31,770 --> 01:22:35,250
and then how we get
the BERT architecture.

1327
01:22:35,250 --> 01:22:38,170
So this is what we had in the
original transformer paper

1328
01:22:38,170 --> 01:22:40,570
that we saw last week.

1329
01:22:40,570 --> 01:22:46,930
And what BERT did is extract
the encoder part of it

1330
01:22:46,930 --> 01:22:52,330
and attach basically these new
objective functions that I just

1331
01:22:52,330 --> 01:22:56,690
mentioned, alongside some
new set of tricks when it

1332
01:22:56,690 --> 01:23:00,850
comes to representing tokens.

1333
01:23:00,850 --> 01:23:08,250
So I think we're going to
go through them one by one.

1334
01:23:08,250 --> 01:23:11,450
So first of all,
one interesting note

1335
01:23:11,450 --> 01:23:15,490
is that it uses a specific
tokenizer called WordPiece.

1336
01:23:15,490 --> 01:23:18,770
So you can see it
as a tokenizer that

1337
01:23:18,770 --> 01:23:25,410
learns on your training set,
based on merge rules that

1338
01:23:25,410 --> 01:23:27,450
maximize the likelihood.

1339
01:23:27,450 --> 01:23:29,470
So basically, you have
some huge training set,

1340
01:23:29,470 --> 01:23:34,730
and you train a tokenizer that
merges atomic tokens together

1341
01:23:34,730 --> 01:23:38,530
to build your target vocabulary.

1342
01:23:38,530 --> 01:23:41,870
And some order of magnitude,
I mentioned o of 30k.

1343
01:23:41,870 --> 01:23:44,690
So it's typically, I
think this is the size

1344
01:23:44,690 --> 01:23:46,730
that they chose in this paper.

1345
01:23:46,730 --> 01:23:51,450
And in general, like vocabulary
sizes in these sorts of paper

1346
01:23:51,450 --> 01:23:54,950
are in the order of magnitude
of 10 to the power of 4,

1347
01:23:54,950 --> 01:23:59,290
10 to the power of 5, except
for our token-free method

1348
01:23:59,290 --> 01:24:03,690
that we saw, like ByT5,
which is like this very

1349
01:24:03,690 --> 01:24:08,450
restricted set of tokens, like 2
to the power of 8, which is 256.

1350
01:24:08,450 --> 01:24:11,970
Apart from this specific
case, you always

1351
01:24:11,970 --> 01:24:14,250
have this order of magnitude.

1352
01:24:18,596 --> 01:24:21,810
And basically, we are going
to make use of the tokens

1353
01:24:21,810 --> 01:24:23,890
that I mentioned.

1354
01:24:23,890 --> 01:24:26,730
Like at the beginning,
so you have the CLS token

1355
01:24:26,730 --> 01:24:30,930
that is going to carry the
bidirectional representation

1356
01:24:30,930 --> 01:24:33,810
of all your sequence.

1357
01:24:33,810 --> 01:24:37,010
And then you have SEP
tokens to separate

1358
01:24:37,010 --> 01:24:42,290
the two sentences towards the
next-sentence prediction task.

1359
01:24:42,290 --> 01:24:47,010
And there is something that I
haven't talked about just yet.

1360
01:24:47,010 --> 01:24:49,450
So I think maybe we
can talk about it

1361
01:24:49,450 --> 01:24:53,070
at the time of the deep dive.

1362
01:24:53,070 --> 01:24:57,730
So in order to have this
masked language model task,

1363
01:24:57,730 --> 01:24:59,830
so of course you need
to mask some tokens.

1364
01:24:59,830 --> 01:25:04,130
So we're going to see the
technique that is basically

1365
01:25:04,130 --> 01:25:09,410
applying these sorts of mask and
where and at which frequency.

1366
01:25:09,410 --> 01:25:13,290
And we're going to see with
respect to the output what

1367
01:25:13,290 --> 01:25:17,690
is going to be our task based
on the resulting representation.

1368
01:25:17,690 --> 01:25:20,630
So I'm just going to
pass quickly on it here,

1369
01:25:20,630 --> 01:25:24,330
but we're going to
come back very soon.

1370
01:25:24,330 --> 01:25:26,610
OK, great.

1371
01:25:26,610 --> 01:25:29,690
So one big piece of news
regarding your input

1372
01:25:29,690 --> 01:25:30,850
embeddings--

1373
01:25:30,850 --> 01:25:33,970
so what stays the same?

1374
01:25:33,970 --> 01:25:37,490
So you still have these
huge dictionary lookup

1375
01:25:37,490 --> 01:25:41,370
of embeddings for each token
that you're going to learn.

1376
01:25:41,370 --> 01:25:45,370
And you're going to additively
add the positional encoding

1377
01:25:45,370 --> 01:25:48,570
that we saw at last lecture.

1378
01:25:48,570 --> 01:25:51,840
And Afshine talked about
earlier in this lecture,

1379
01:25:51,840 --> 01:25:56,220
which can either be
hard-coded or learned.

1380
01:25:56,220 --> 01:26:02,500
I think the authors here just
used a hard-coded version here,

1381
01:26:02,500 --> 01:26:03,900
but I'm not too sure.

1382
01:26:03,900 --> 01:26:07,300
But it's roughly the
same performance usually.

1383
01:26:07,300 --> 01:26:09,620
But there is something new.

1384
01:26:09,620 --> 01:26:13,180
There is the introduction
of a new kind

1385
01:26:13,180 --> 01:26:17,780
of encoding called segment
encoding that is going to still

1386
01:26:17,780 --> 01:26:23,340
be additively added to tokens,
with the exception that we just

1387
01:26:23,340 --> 01:26:26,480
have two possible
encodings there.

1388
01:26:26,480 --> 01:26:30,320
So you have segment A that
represents the first sentence,

1389
01:26:30,320 --> 01:26:33,660
and then segment B that
represents the second sentence.

1390
01:26:33,660 --> 01:26:37,540
And it's supposed to
help with the NSP task

1391
01:26:37,540 --> 01:26:42,220
to represent what could be
features that can helpfully

1392
01:26:42,220 --> 01:26:46,300
represent a sentence that
precedes another one.

1393
01:26:46,300 --> 01:26:48,660
So at least that
was the hypothesis

1394
01:26:48,660 --> 01:26:50,140
admitted by the authors.

1395
01:26:50,140 --> 01:26:53,460
We're going to see it has
been challenged later on.

1396
01:26:53,460 --> 01:26:55,500
But this is one of
the key concepts

1397
01:26:55,500 --> 01:26:59,060
that was introduced here.

1398
01:26:59,060 --> 01:27:02,440
Any questions so far?

1399
01:27:02,440 --> 01:27:02,940
Yep.

1400
01:27:28,300 --> 01:27:29,600
Yep, so a great point.

1401
01:27:29,600 --> 01:27:34,167
So the question is, what does
segment encoding do at all?

1402
01:27:34,167 --> 01:27:36,000
So it's basically
something that is learned.

1403
01:27:36,000 --> 01:27:39,420
So you have two
indices, two basically

1404
01:27:39,420 --> 01:27:41,000
embeddings that you can learn.

1405
01:27:41,000 --> 01:27:43,900
You just additively
add them, segment

1406
01:27:43,900 --> 01:27:47,620
A for tokens in the first
part of the sentence,

1407
01:27:47,620 --> 01:27:49,740
and then segment B
in the second part.

1408
01:27:49,740 --> 01:27:53,440
And you just learn it
with gradient descent.

1409
01:27:53,440 --> 01:27:56,180
So you do nothing with it.

1410
01:27:56,180 --> 01:27:58,040
I think there was
another question here?

1411
01:27:58,040 --> 01:27:58,540
Yeah.

1412
01:28:07,580 --> 01:28:08,280
That's right.

1413
01:28:08,280 --> 01:28:11,513
So the question is, is every
token in the same sentence

1414
01:28:11,513 --> 01:28:13,180
going to have the
same segment encoding?

1415
01:28:13,180 --> 01:28:16,340
Yes, yeah.

1416
01:28:16,340 --> 01:28:17,800
OK, awesome.

1417
01:28:17,800 --> 01:28:22,660
So I'm seeing I might need
to speed up a tiny bit.

1418
01:28:22,660 --> 01:28:25,540
So yeah, the second thing
that I want to highlight here

1419
01:28:25,540 --> 01:28:29,180
is that we take the encoder
part of the transformer.

1420
01:28:29,180 --> 01:28:31,480
And nothing new here.

1421
01:28:31,480 --> 01:28:32,640
It's just the same.

1422
01:28:32,640 --> 01:28:37,820
We have self-attention,
followed by these FFN.

1423
01:28:37,820 --> 01:28:41,260
So this is where you're going
to get your bidirectional nature

1424
01:28:41,260 --> 01:28:43,700
of your encodings.

1425
01:28:43,700 --> 01:28:45,580
And then basically
we're assuming

1426
01:28:45,580 --> 01:28:49,860
that training both
MLM and NSP on it

1427
01:28:49,860 --> 01:28:54,540
is going to help us
learn helpful projection

1428
01:28:54,540 --> 01:28:57,380
matrices in this encoder
that can be suited

1429
01:28:57,380 --> 01:28:58,890
for any classification task.

1430
01:29:01,660 --> 01:29:02,520
OK, great.

1431
01:29:02,520 --> 01:29:08,140
And as promised, I talked
about detailing more about what

1432
01:29:08,140 --> 01:29:10,660
this MLM task was going to do.

1433
01:29:10,660 --> 01:29:15,180
So when you look at
the input, you're

1434
01:29:15,180 --> 01:29:19,620
going to basically have
your input sentence,

1435
01:29:19,620 --> 01:29:23,940
and replace at
random some tokens.

1436
01:29:23,940 --> 01:29:27,980
So it will be replaced
either with the token mask.

1437
01:29:27,980 --> 01:29:31,220
So it's in 80% of the time.

1438
01:29:31,220 --> 01:29:33,860
In 10% of the time,
the tokens selected

1439
01:29:33,860 --> 01:29:38,300
for this MLM objective
function are not

1440
01:29:38,300 --> 01:29:39,570
going to be replaced at all.

1441
01:29:39,570 --> 01:29:41,320
So we're just saying,
it's the same token,

1442
01:29:41,320 --> 01:29:43,660
just predict the same token.

1443
01:29:43,660 --> 01:29:45,820
And then 10% of the
time, it's going

1444
01:29:45,820 --> 01:29:49,540
to be changed to some
random other word.

1445
01:29:49,540 --> 01:29:52,180
So at the end of it,
you have the subset

1446
01:29:52,180 --> 01:29:55,640
of tokens you're going to
perform your MLM task on.

1447
01:29:55,640 --> 01:29:59,220
And then this is
how it's composed.

1448
01:29:59,220 --> 01:30:00,460
OK, great.

1449
01:30:00,460 --> 01:30:04,340
And so basically
the intuition here

1450
01:30:04,340 --> 01:30:07,980
is that when you want to
predict what a token is,

1451
01:30:07,980 --> 01:30:10,120
you need to know
about its context.

1452
01:30:10,120 --> 01:30:12,740
So we're going to
force the model

1453
01:30:12,740 --> 01:30:15,560
to learn about what
surrounds it, left and right.

1454
01:30:15,560 --> 01:30:20,820
So this is the bidirectional
property of this architecture

1455
01:30:20,820 --> 01:30:21,570
put into action.

1456
01:30:24,460 --> 01:30:25,620
OK, great.

1457
01:30:25,620 --> 01:30:28,220
And now we're going to talk
about the next-sentence

1458
01:30:28,220 --> 01:30:33,660
prediction task where
basically the process here

1459
01:30:33,660 --> 01:30:37,460
is to select two sentences
from a given corpus,

1460
01:30:37,460 --> 01:30:44,140
and then present them side by
side in order 50% of the time,

1461
01:30:44,140 --> 01:30:49,400
and in some random order
the other part of the time.

1462
01:30:49,400 --> 01:30:53,020
And the goal is for
some classification head

1463
01:30:53,020 --> 01:30:57,660
on top of the CLS token to
determine whether A and B are

1464
01:30:57,660 --> 01:30:58,980
consecutive.

1465
01:30:58,980 --> 01:31:02,100
So that's all it does.

1466
01:31:02,100 --> 01:31:05,500
And so the assumption
is that it also helps

1467
01:31:05,500 --> 01:31:07,120
learn some useful embeddings.

1468
01:31:09,900 --> 01:31:11,160
OK, great.

1469
01:31:11,160 --> 01:31:15,100
And here I'm going to
present the notation that

1470
01:31:15,100 --> 01:31:16,360
is used in the paper.

1471
01:31:16,360 --> 01:31:18,280
So the paper is something
I recommend reading.

1472
01:31:18,280 --> 01:31:21,520
It's a very nice read, alongside
the "Attention is All You Need."

1473
01:31:21,520 --> 01:31:24,740
I would say it's
a landmark paper.

1474
01:31:24,740 --> 01:31:31,060
I think it has a 170k citations,
something really impressive.

1475
01:31:31,060 --> 01:31:35,260
And basically what we called
n in the original transformer

1476
01:31:35,260 --> 01:31:40,580
paper is now called L. H,
that was called d model,

1477
01:31:40,580 --> 01:31:43,640
is the dimension
of our embeddings.

1478
01:31:43,640 --> 01:31:47,440
And A is the number
of attention heads,

1479
01:31:47,440 --> 01:31:49,980
which was called the little h.

1480
01:31:49,980 --> 01:31:53,620
So here I'm just showing these
new notations for information,

1481
01:31:53,620 --> 01:31:55,160
just to give you the mapping.

1482
01:31:55,160 --> 01:31:57,220
But of course,
together with Afshine,

1483
01:31:57,220 --> 01:32:00,460
we're going to stay consistent
with the original notations we

1484
01:32:00,460 --> 01:32:04,140
had, so just like
for information.

1485
01:32:04,140 --> 01:32:06,700
And one interesting
note is that you

1486
01:32:06,700 --> 01:32:09,340
will see that the
BERT model, when

1487
01:32:09,340 --> 01:32:14,060
you look at some repository of
models such as Hugging Face,

1488
01:32:14,060 --> 01:32:17,260
so usually it's given
in several versions.

1489
01:32:17,260 --> 01:32:20,620
So you will see sometimes
like case, uncased.

1490
01:32:20,620 --> 01:32:23,100
So this denotes what
kind of preprocessing

1491
01:32:23,100 --> 01:32:25,500
was done to the data,
whether you only

1492
01:32:25,500 --> 01:32:30,980
have lowercase words in there
or whether casing matters.

1493
01:32:30,980 --> 01:32:34,340
So based on your
task of interest,

1494
01:32:34,340 --> 01:32:38,780
it might be one thing
you want to choose from.

1495
01:32:38,780 --> 01:32:41,060
OK, great.

1496
01:32:41,060 --> 01:32:43,380
And I give some
orders of magnitude

1497
01:32:43,380 --> 01:32:51,340
from the paper on what values
were chosen for each of these.

1498
01:32:51,340 --> 01:32:53,980
So if I remember
correctly, I think

1499
01:32:53,980 --> 01:33:00,740
the original transformer had 12
stacked encoders and decoders.

1500
01:33:00,740 --> 01:33:04,770
So I think some numbers
here were taken from there.

1501
01:33:08,860 --> 01:33:13,640
So yeah, order of magnitude
is 100 million parameters.

1502
01:33:16,540 --> 01:33:17,720
Any questions so far?

1503
01:33:21,460 --> 01:33:24,020
OK, great.

1504
01:33:24,020 --> 01:33:28,940
And then now we're going to
talk about the fine-tuning stage

1505
01:33:28,940 --> 01:33:33,940
where the goal is
to basically take

1506
01:33:33,940 --> 01:33:37,460
whatever we have learned
at pre-training stage,

1507
01:33:37,460 --> 01:33:39,580
and then freeze those weights.

1508
01:33:39,580 --> 01:33:43,000
And instead of training
again on those same weights,

1509
01:33:43,000 --> 01:33:45,660
you have some
classification linear layer

1510
01:33:45,660 --> 01:33:48,660
that is put on top of
either the CLS token

1511
01:33:48,660 --> 01:33:50,900
or on top of tokens of interest.

1512
01:33:50,900 --> 01:33:54,880
And you're going to learn about
the linear embeddings there.

1513
01:33:54,880 --> 01:33:57,980
So you're going to have
some classification task.

1514
01:33:57,980 --> 01:34:01,060
So you could either freeze
all these pre-trained weights

1515
01:34:01,060 --> 01:34:03,980
and just train on
these small weights.

1516
01:34:03,980 --> 01:34:06,240
Or you can just retrain
the whole thing.

1517
01:34:06,240 --> 01:34:09,100
I think there is multiple
classification schemes.

1518
01:34:09,100 --> 01:34:13,260
And some of it will be
influenced by your willingness

1519
01:34:13,260 --> 01:34:15,900
to retrain a lot of
the network and how

1520
01:34:15,900 --> 01:34:19,020
different the classification
task is with respect

1521
01:34:19,020 --> 01:34:20,450
to the original
pre-training task.

1522
01:34:23,540 --> 01:34:24,720
OK, great.

1523
01:34:24,720 --> 01:34:27,500
And then just to give
some examples of what

1524
01:34:27,500 --> 01:34:31,700
could be fine-tuning tasks
for tasks of interest,

1525
01:34:31,700 --> 01:34:33,620
you can have a
sentiment extraction

1526
01:34:33,620 --> 01:34:39,270
where you build a classification
layer on top of the CLS token.

1527
01:34:39,270 --> 01:34:43,750
And we give some other
example question answering

1528
01:34:43,750 --> 01:34:46,930
where basically you
are given some input.

1529
01:34:46,930 --> 01:34:51,350
And the goal of the model is
to detect beginning and end

1530
01:34:51,350 --> 01:34:53,090
spans of the response.

1531
01:34:53,090 --> 01:34:55,550
So it's basically some
objective function

1532
01:34:55,550 --> 01:34:59,230
that is at the token level.

1533
01:34:59,230 --> 01:35:00,510
OK, great.

1534
01:35:00,510 --> 01:35:05,110
So now I propose that
we do some deep dive

1535
01:35:05,110 --> 01:35:09,150
into one specific example.

1536
01:35:09,150 --> 01:35:13,270
Our favorite example, this
teddy bear is so cute.

1537
01:35:13,270 --> 01:35:17,870
Let's just see how
BERT works in practice.

1538
01:35:17,870 --> 01:35:21,990
So basically what you would
do in an uncased setting

1539
01:35:21,990 --> 01:35:26,470
is take the sentence,
pre-process it, just

1540
01:35:26,470 --> 01:35:28,870
put everything lowercase.

1541
01:35:28,870 --> 01:35:32,190
Then you apply the
WordPiece algorithm

1542
01:35:32,190 --> 01:35:37,630
on whatever tokenization
mechanism that your tokenizer

1543
01:35:37,630 --> 01:35:38,570
has learned.

1544
01:35:38,570 --> 01:35:42,090
So for example here, apparently
it had all these merge rules.

1545
01:35:42,090 --> 01:35:46,510
So this is the tokens that
appear in the vocabulary.

1546
01:35:46,510 --> 01:35:51,230
And then as I promised, we add
the CLS token at the beginning.

1547
01:35:51,230 --> 01:35:54,630
And then we add the SEP token.

1548
01:35:54,630 --> 01:35:58,430
And you also have
this PAD tokens

1549
01:35:58,430 --> 01:36:05,590
that are basically used to fill
out the sequence until the end.

1550
01:36:05,590 --> 01:36:07,690
Because when you train,
you train by batch,

1551
01:36:07,690 --> 01:36:10,350
and then batches are
composed of matrices

1552
01:36:10,350 --> 01:36:13,510
that have a fixed length.

1553
01:36:13,510 --> 01:36:15,030
Yeah.

1554
01:36:15,030 --> 01:36:17,550
So let's just have
this deep dive a bit

1555
01:36:17,550 --> 01:36:23,090
the same as what we had in the
transformer deep dive last time.

1556
01:36:23,090 --> 01:36:25,730
So you have the embeddings
that are learned.

1557
01:36:25,730 --> 01:36:31,150
So it's some huge lookup table
between the index of each token

1558
01:36:31,150 --> 01:36:33,430
and the learned representation.

1559
01:36:33,430 --> 01:36:37,750
So you add to it the position
embedding of the token.

1560
01:36:37,750 --> 01:36:40,250
And something that's new here--

1561
01:36:40,250 --> 01:36:41,670
the segment embedding.

1562
01:36:41,670 --> 01:36:44,430
So exactly as we said,
it's an embedding

1563
01:36:44,430 --> 01:36:47,070
that is added to each token.

1564
01:36:47,070 --> 01:36:50,150
And the same embedding is
added to the same tokens.

1565
01:36:50,150 --> 01:36:54,150
So all the tokens have
the same segment A.

1566
01:36:54,150 --> 01:36:57,590
Then some other embedding B
is added to all the tokens

1567
01:36:57,590 --> 01:37:02,710
of the segment B. OK, great.

1568
01:37:02,710 --> 01:37:06,070
So now you have, similarly
as the transformer,

1569
01:37:06,070 --> 01:37:10,270
something that is position-aware
and context-aware--

1570
01:37:10,270 --> 01:37:15,310
so not context-aware just
yet, but segment-aware here.

1571
01:37:15,310 --> 01:37:16,870
OK, great.

1572
01:37:16,870 --> 01:37:22,950
And basically it goes through
this encoder architecture.

1573
01:37:22,950 --> 01:37:24,830
And then at the end
of it, for the case

1574
01:37:24,830 --> 01:37:27,430
of sentiment
extraction, we do not

1575
01:37:27,430 --> 01:37:30,470
care about the
embeddings that are

1576
01:37:30,470 --> 01:37:35,030
corresponding to each token
that is not the CLS token.

1577
01:37:35,030 --> 01:37:39,950
Because what we care about is
the output embedding of the CLS

1578
01:37:39,950 --> 01:37:44,550
token, where we
plug a linear layer

1579
01:37:44,550 --> 01:37:47,800
that will learn some
classification task.

1580
01:37:50,710 --> 01:37:51,930
So any question here?

1581
01:37:55,310 --> 01:37:59,990
So does the fact that we drop
all the output embeddings, apart

1582
01:37:59,990 --> 01:38:02,590
from the CLS token, make sense?

1583
01:38:02,590 --> 01:38:11,690
Yeah, yep.

1584
01:38:21,190 --> 01:38:25,930
Yeah, so the question is, what
does this FFN, is that right?

1585
01:38:25,930 --> 01:38:27,450
What does this
FFN correspond to?

1586
01:38:27,450 --> 01:38:31,150
So basically you have a
map between the dimension

1587
01:38:31,150 --> 01:38:34,610
of the output embedding
and your task of interest.

1588
01:38:34,610 --> 01:38:40,890
So it might be classification
of either positive or negative.

1589
01:38:40,890 --> 01:38:44,350
So you have some hidden
layer with some length.

1590
01:38:44,350 --> 01:38:46,190
So you have typically
two matrices

1591
01:38:46,190 --> 01:38:49,550
to learn the projection from one
to that hidden layer, and then

1592
01:38:49,550 --> 01:38:51,450
the hidden layer to the output.

1593
01:38:51,450 --> 01:38:53,230
And then you learn
these weights in order

1594
01:38:53,230 --> 01:38:56,298
to do the classification
task, based on the embeddings

1595
01:38:56,298 --> 01:38:57,340
that it has learned here.

1596
01:38:59,990 --> 01:39:00,978
Yeah, great question.

1597
01:39:00,978 --> 01:39:02,770
So that was the question
I was waiting for.

1598
01:39:02,770 --> 01:39:05,830
So the question is, why
do we throw away all

1599
01:39:05,830 --> 01:39:08,650
these other output embeddings?

1600
01:39:08,650 --> 01:39:11,110
So we don't need them here.

1601
01:39:11,110 --> 01:39:12,910
So we are in a
classification task.

1602
01:39:12,910 --> 01:39:19,630
We have put as convention to
operate on top of some token,

1603
01:39:19,630 --> 01:39:21,150
like the CLS token.

1604
01:39:21,150 --> 01:39:22,750
And then the magic
of this token is

1605
01:39:22,750 --> 01:39:25,470
that all these self-attention
mechanisms that

1606
01:39:25,470 --> 01:39:30,110
are in the encoder has mixed
the representation of each

1607
01:39:30,110 --> 01:39:34,150
of the other tokens in
that representation, such

1608
01:39:34,150 --> 01:39:39,110
that the output embeddings,
they are context-aware.

1609
01:39:39,110 --> 01:39:41,190
So basically, it's
an embedding that is

1610
01:39:41,190 --> 01:39:43,590
geared towards classification.

1611
01:39:43,590 --> 01:39:46,590
And this is what we
say will be what we

1612
01:39:46,590 --> 01:39:51,390
plug in to that linear layer.

1613
01:39:51,390 --> 01:39:56,190
And so when I say we throw
out all the other embeddings,

1614
01:39:56,190 --> 01:39:58,150
it's actually
something that we do

1615
01:39:58,150 --> 01:39:59,810
for the case of classification.

1616
01:39:59,810 --> 01:40:02,470
But if we do classification
at the token level,

1617
01:40:02,470 --> 01:40:04,530
then each of them may be used.

1618
01:40:04,530 --> 01:40:07,510
So for example, when I say
question answering, if you want

1619
01:40:07,510 --> 01:40:14,910
to detect whether a given token
is the beginning of an answer,

1620
01:40:14,910 --> 01:40:16,430
beginning of end
of an answer, you

1621
01:40:16,430 --> 01:40:19,990
would typically
have two FFNs that

1622
01:40:19,990 --> 01:40:23,170
respectively predict the
start and end of the answer.

1623
01:40:23,170 --> 01:40:25,890
And you would apply it on
each of these embeddings.

1624
01:40:29,430 --> 01:40:31,130
Any other questions?

1625
01:40:31,130 --> 01:40:31,630
Yep.

1626
01:40:37,430 --> 01:40:40,790
So the question is, what is
query, key, and value for CLS?

1627
01:40:40,790 --> 01:40:44,890
So it's going to be the same
process as all the other tokens.

1628
01:40:44,890 --> 01:40:47,310
So you learn here
a representation

1629
01:40:47,310 --> 01:40:50,630
for the embedding,
for the token CLS.

1630
01:40:50,630 --> 01:40:53,090
It gets projected to query.

1631
01:40:53,090 --> 01:40:54,250
It gets projected to key.

1632
01:40:54,250 --> 01:40:56,190
It gets projected to value.

1633
01:40:56,190 --> 01:40:59,030
It does all its
attention computation.

1634
01:40:59,030 --> 01:41:01,470
And at the end, you
get this embedding

1635
01:41:01,470 --> 01:41:06,090
that basically that has
attended to all the other ones.

1636
01:41:06,090 --> 01:41:08,670
So it's like the answer
is, it's the same as

1637
01:41:08,670 --> 01:41:11,310
for the other tokens.

1638
01:41:11,310 --> 01:41:12,110
So, yeah.

1639
01:41:12,110 --> 01:41:15,550
So just treat it as one
token, it could be any token,

1640
01:41:15,550 --> 01:41:18,790
and it's the same.

1641
01:41:18,790 --> 01:41:19,530
OK, awesome.

1642
01:41:19,530 --> 01:41:21,470
So I see we have
five more minutes.

1643
01:41:21,470 --> 01:41:26,030
And I'm going to quickly
go through the end of it.

1644
01:41:26,030 --> 01:41:29,470
And one thing that
was great with BERT,

1645
01:41:29,470 --> 01:41:32,470
and it was also
great with ELMo, is

1646
01:41:32,470 --> 01:41:35,870
that you have embeddings
that are contextual.

1647
01:41:35,870 --> 01:41:39,230
And here you can see
that it's very easy

1648
01:41:39,230 --> 01:41:42,030
to learn any classification
task that you want,

1649
01:41:42,030 --> 01:41:43,910
based on these learn embeddings.

1650
01:41:43,910 --> 01:41:48,670
So this is a flexibility that
was greatly appreciated here.

1651
01:41:48,670 --> 01:41:52,310
And it's widely used
in the industry.

1652
01:41:52,310 --> 01:41:55,270
So anything that comes
with sentiment detection

1653
01:41:55,270 --> 01:41:58,350
or other
classification-related tasks,

1654
01:41:58,350 --> 01:42:03,790
it's very common to use a
BERT-like model nowadays.

1655
01:42:03,790 --> 01:42:08,550
And I'm going to talk a bit
about its limitations now.

1656
01:42:08,550 --> 01:42:12,170
So as you see in
the original paper,

1657
01:42:12,170 --> 01:42:16,630
I think the context
length was of size 512.

1658
01:42:16,630 --> 01:42:20,750
So it was typically limited
in this early paper.

1659
01:42:20,750 --> 01:42:23,790
Afshine has mentioned
of techniques

1660
01:42:23,790 --> 01:42:26,870
as to how we can further
grow this context

1661
01:42:26,870 --> 01:42:31,030
size without making the
complexity go completely,

1662
01:42:31,030 --> 01:42:35,590
basically like hike.

1663
01:42:35,590 --> 01:42:38,430
And then you have some
approximation methods

1664
01:42:38,430 --> 01:42:40,930
where you compute local
attention, and so on.

1665
01:42:40,930 --> 01:42:43,350
And then the use of
these tricks helps

1666
01:42:43,350 --> 01:42:45,750
you grow the size of the
context while staying

1667
01:42:45,750 --> 01:42:50,510
within reasonable computation
requirement bounds.

1668
01:42:50,510 --> 01:42:53,790
And I'm going to talk
about two other limitations

1669
01:42:53,790 --> 01:42:58,030
that we're going to see what
other models try to remedy.

1670
01:42:58,030 --> 01:43:02,450
So there is one where the
latency could be seen as high.

1671
01:43:02,450 --> 01:43:06,930
You have a still 110 million
parameters for a BERT base,

1672
01:43:06,930 --> 01:43:07,990
so it's quite a lot.

1673
01:43:07,990 --> 01:43:11,910
Is there a way to make
this smaller and faster?

1674
01:43:11,910 --> 01:43:14,830
And then the second
one is basically

1675
01:43:14,830 --> 01:43:19,710
you have these two objective
functions of MLM and NSP.

1676
01:43:19,710 --> 01:43:21,530
Are those two truly helpful?

1677
01:43:21,530 --> 01:43:24,600
Is there any way we can simplify
the pre-training process?

1678
01:43:24,600 --> 01:43:27,500
So we're going to
see in a second how.

1679
01:43:30,240 --> 01:43:37,840
So first, regarding this
second limitation that we had,

1680
01:43:37,840 --> 01:43:41,720
this basically
sensitivity to cost.

1681
01:43:41,720 --> 01:43:45,820
So who here has heard
of distillation?

1682
01:43:49,800 --> 01:43:51,320
Good, few people.

1683
01:43:51,320 --> 01:43:54,680
So I just want to
flash this quote

1684
01:43:54,680 --> 01:44:00,320
from Hinton, Vinyals,
and Jeff Dean, which

1685
01:44:00,320 --> 01:44:02,800
I think has been informative.

1686
01:44:02,800 --> 01:44:06,200
And it's a good
mindset to have to see

1687
01:44:06,200 --> 01:44:10,080
that the distribution that
is output by a given model

1688
01:44:10,080 --> 01:44:14,360
is actually super helpful
to know what it has learned.

1689
01:44:14,360 --> 01:44:17,540
So the soft targets contain
almost all the knowledge.

1690
01:44:17,540 --> 01:44:23,640
So it's some lecture from
them that contain this quote.

1691
01:44:23,640 --> 01:44:26,800
So basically they were at
the origin of the concept

1692
01:44:26,800 --> 01:44:28,640
of distillation later on.

1693
01:44:28,640 --> 01:44:32,560
And you quickly see in practice
that basically learning

1694
01:44:32,560 --> 01:44:37,800
the distribution of a model
is more helpful than directly

1695
01:44:37,800 --> 01:44:40,760
learning the hard labels.

1696
01:44:40,760 --> 01:44:45,640
So you have this concept of
teacher and student models,

1697
01:44:45,640 --> 01:44:49,080
where basically the
goal in distillation

1698
01:44:49,080 --> 01:44:53,520
is going to be to map this
output distribution of a smaller

1699
01:44:53,520 --> 01:44:57,120
model directly to your
more complex model,

1700
01:44:57,120 --> 01:45:00,000
rather than the hard labels.

1701
01:45:00,000 --> 01:45:04,560
And the objective
function that you

1702
01:45:04,560 --> 01:45:09,000
use for this to minimize this
is the KL divergence, which

1703
01:45:09,000 --> 01:45:15,840
basically says in a world that
is described by the teacher,

1704
01:45:15,840 --> 01:45:22,640
the teacher T, how bad is it
to model with the student S.

1705
01:45:22,640 --> 01:45:27,080
So it basically tries to
assess how close the student

1706
01:45:27,080 --> 01:45:30,520
distribution is going
to be to the world's T.

1707
01:45:30,520 --> 01:45:33,360
And one interesting note
that you will see here

1708
01:45:33,360 --> 01:45:36,560
is that you find the
cross-entropy loss

1709
01:45:36,560 --> 01:45:40,980
if your yT distribution
is just a hard label.

1710
01:45:40,980 --> 01:45:43,680
So if you have just
a 1 at one position

1711
01:45:43,680 --> 01:45:46,560
and then 0 everywhere
else, you have

1712
01:45:46,560 --> 01:45:52,480
minus log of yS, which
is very interesting.

1713
01:45:52,480 --> 01:45:55,800
And then what the
DistilBERT folks have done--

1714
01:45:55,800 --> 01:45:57,500
so by the way, it's
a very clean paper,

1715
01:45:57,500 --> 01:46:00,720
it's like four pages,
but super impactful.

1716
01:46:00,720 --> 01:46:06,360
So it says that if you reduce
the number of layers by 2,

1717
01:46:06,360 --> 01:46:10,840
you have a lot of gains and
almost the same performance,

1718
01:46:10,840 --> 01:46:13,260
which is very remarkable.

1719
01:46:13,260 --> 01:46:15,800
And they basically used
distillation as a way

1720
01:46:15,800 --> 01:46:17,640
to retain that performance.

1721
01:46:17,640 --> 01:46:21,320
So this has been like the
key, alongside diminishing

1722
01:46:21,320 --> 01:46:23,280
the number of layers.

1723
01:46:23,280 --> 01:46:27,160
And last, I'm going
to talk about RoBERTa.

1724
01:46:27,160 --> 01:46:32,600
That studied the fact that
removing the NSP objective

1725
01:46:32,600 --> 01:46:36,900
function led to no decrease
in performance almost.

1726
01:46:36,900 --> 01:46:38,360
So they just dropped it.

1727
01:46:38,360 --> 01:46:43,280
And they added some tricks,
such as dynamically doing

1728
01:46:43,280 --> 01:46:44,360
the masking.

1729
01:46:44,360 --> 01:46:46,680
So for example, for a
given piece of text,

1730
01:46:46,680 --> 01:46:50,040
at each epoch, so every time
